{"title_page": "Piula Theological College", "text_new": "[[File:Piula Theological College, Upolu island, Samoa, 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|230px|Piula Chapel]]\n[[File:Piula college grounds 2010.JPG|thumb|right|230px|College grounds.]]\n'''Piula Theological College''' is a [[Methodist]] training institution in [[Samoa]]. It was established in 1868 in [[Lufilufi]] on the north coast of [[Upolu]] island after its initial beginnings in 1859 at [[Satupa'itea]] on the south coast of [[Savai'i]] island. The Methodist Mission in Samoa purchased the land at the Methodist leaning district and later named their training center Piula Theological College. The name ''Piula'' is a [[transliteration]] of the [[biblical]] name ''Beulah''<ref name=bk1>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tckqy2TMjqoC&pg=PA127&dq=Piula+Theological+College,+Lufilufi&lr=&cd=10#v=onepage&q=Piula%20Theological%20College%2C%20Lufilufi&f=false\n|title=Samoan women: widening choices\n|first=Peggy\n|last=Fairbairn-Dunlop\n|page=127\n|year=2003\n|publisher=University of the South Pacific\n|isbn=982-02-0360-0\n|accessdate=2 February 2010\n}}</ref> which means ''married'' (to the Lord).\n\nThe college includes the recently renovated historic Piula chapel, large open grounds, and Samoan [[Architecture of Samoa|fale]]. At the front of the chapel are steps leading down to the sea where ''Fatumea'', the oval [[Piula Cave Pool]] is, a popular swimming hole for locals and visitors.\n\n==History==\nIn Samoa, the Methodist religion is referred to as 'lotu tonga' through the early initial contact with converts and the church's mission in [[Tonga]] during the early 19th century.<ref name=pi>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gB9mHNE17jgC&pg=PA197&dq=Lotu+Tonga+Methodist&cd=3#v=onepage&q=Lotu%20Tonga%20Methodist&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|first=Donald Denoon, Malama Meleisea, Stewart Firth, Jocelyn Linnekin|last=Karen Nero|page=197|year=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-00354-7|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to set up the training institution came about from an annual church meeting held on [[Manono Island]], a stronghold of the church at the time, on 21 September 1859.<ref name=bk1/>\n\nA key figure during the early years of the Methodist church in Samoa was the [[George Brown (missionary)|Rev. George Brown]] who lived in Samoa for 14 years, between 1860 and 1874. He worked with his wife Lydia at the mission in [[Satupa'itea]] on [[Savai'i]] island. Brown learned the [[Samoan language]] and regarded the people as his friends. Like many other missionaries to the Pacific, Brown recorded his experience in Samoa in journals which include significant historical information about the Methodist church and Samoan history and culture.<ref name=am>{{cite web |url = http://www.adam-matthew-publications.co.uk/digital_guides/pacific_island_culture/Publishers-Note.aspx |work = Adam Matthew Publications |title = Pacific Island Culture and Society, Publisher's Note |accessdate  = 6 February 2010\n |url-status = dead |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101018063328/http://www.adam-matthew-publications.co.uk/digital_guides/pacific_island_culture/Publishers-Note.aspx |archivedate = 18 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nThe theological college offers a four-year course leading to a Diploma in Theological Studies with the possibility of going on to secure a Bachelor of Divinity degree. The training prepares people for Ministry in the Samoa Methodist Church. Some of the students are married and the wives undertake courses to prepare them for the role they will play as minister's wives.\n\nA guiding principle to all college activity has been the notion that Piula should be, as near as possible, a Christian village. Students are taught how to take part in a proper manner in Samoan custom and society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piulapublications.com\n|work=Piula Theological College Handbook|title=Piula College One Hundred Years 1868-1968|accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nOn [[Upolu]] island, the college is 26&nbsp;km east along the northern coastal road from the capital [[Apia]]. Entry to the campus is through a blue and yellow painted stone wall beside the main island road.\n\n<gallery widths=180px heights=180px perrow=4 caption=\"Gallery\">\nFile:Rev George Brown c. 1908.jpg|[[George Brown (missionary)|George Brown]] (1835-1917), a founder of the college.\nFile:Large stone Methodist church, Satupaitea, Samoa c. 1908.jpg|Methodist stone church, [[Satupa'itea]], c. 1908\nFile:Piula Cave Pool, Upolu island, Samoa.jpg|[[Piula Cave Pool]] by the sea below the chapel.\nFile:Samoan lali log drums at Piula Theological College.JPG|''Lali'', Samoan wooden log drums, each 2m long used to beat out sound and signal times.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Religion in Samoa]]\n*[[Architecture of Samoa]]\n*[[History of Samoa]]\n*[[German Samoa]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Samoa}}\n{{South Pacific Association of Theological Schools}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Methodism in Samoa]]\n[[Category:Methodist seminaries and theological colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Samoa]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in Samoa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Atua (district)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Piula Theological College, Upolu island, Samoa, 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|230px|Piula Chapel]]\n[[File:Piula college grounds 2010.JPG|thumb|right|230px|College grounds.]]\n'''Piula Theological College''' is a [[Methodist]] training institution in [[Samoa]]. It was established in 1868 in [[Lufilufi]] on the north coast of [[Upolu]] island after its initial beginnings in 1859 at [[Satupa'itea]] on the south coast of [[Savai'i]] island. The Methodist Mission in Samoa purchased the land at the Methodist leaning district and later named their training center Piula Theological College. The name ''Piula'' is a [[transliteration]] of the [[biblical]] name ''Beulah''<ref name=bk1>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tckqy2TMjqoC&pg=PA127&dq=Piula+Theological+College,+Lufilufi&lr=&cd=10#v=onepage&q=Piula%20Theological%20College%2C%20Lufilufi&f=false\n|title=Samoan women: widening choices\n|first=Peggy\n|last=Fairbairn-Dunlop\n|page=127\n|year=2003\n|publisher=University of the South Pacific\n|isbn=982-02-0360-0\n|accessdate=2 February 2010\n}}</ref> which means ''married'' (to the Lord).\n\nThe college includes the recently renovated historic Piula chapel, large open grounds, and Samoan [[Architecture of Samoa|fale]]. At the front of the chapel are steps leading down to the sea where ''Fatumea'', the oval [[Piula Cave Pool]] is, a popular swimming hole for locals and visitors.\n\n==History==\nIn Samoa, the Methodist religion is referred to as 'lotu tonga' through the early initial contact with converts and the church's mission in [[Tonga]] during the early 19th century.<ref name=pi>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gB9mHNE17jgC&pg=PA197&dq=Lotu+Tonga+Methodist&cd=3#v=onepage&q=Lotu%20Tonga%20Methodist&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|first=Donald Denoon, Malama Meleisea, Stewart Firth, Jocelyn Linnekin|last=Karen Nero|page=197|year=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-00354-7|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to set up the training institution came about from an annual church meeting held on [[Manono Island]], a stronghold of the church at the time, on 21 September 1859.<ref name=bk1/>\n\nA key figure during the early years of the Methodist church in Samoa was the [[George Brown (missionary)|Rev. George Brown]] who lived in Samoa for 14 years, between 1860 and 1874. He worked with his wife Lydia at the mission in [[Satupa'itea]] on [[Savai'i]] island. Brown learned the [[Samoan language]] and regarded the people as his friends. Like many other missionaries to the Pacific, Brown recorded his experience in Samoa in journals which include significant historical information about the Methodist church and Samoan history and culture.<ref name=am>{{cite web |url = http://www.adam-matthew-publications.co.uk/digital_guides/pacific_island_culture/Publishers-Note.aspx |work = Adam Matthew Publications |title = Pacific Island Culture and Society, Publisher's Note |accessdate  = 6 February 2010\n |url-status = dead |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101018063328/http://www.adam-matthew-publications.co.uk/digital_guides/pacific_island_culture/Publishers-Note.aspx |archivedate = 18 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nThe theological college offers a four-year course leading to a Diploma in Theological Studies with the possibility of going on to secure a Bachelor of Divinity degree. The training prepares people for Ministry in the Samoa Methodist Church. Some of the students are married and the wives undertake courses to prepare them for the role they will play as minister's wives.\n\nA guiding principle to all college activity has been the notion that Piula should be, as near as possible, a Christian village. Students are taught how to take part in a proper manner in Samoan custom and society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piulapublications.com\n|work=Piula Theological College Handbook|title=Piula College One Hundred Years 1868-1968|accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nOn [[Upolu]] island, the college is 26&nbsp;km east along the northern coastal road from the capital [[Apia]]. Entry to the campus is through a blue and yellow painted stone wall beside the main island road.\n\n<gallery widths=180px heights=180px perrow=4 caption=\"Gallery\">\nFile:Rev George Brown c. 1908.jpg|[[George Brown (missionary)|George Brown]] (1835-1917), a founder of the college.\nFile:Large stone Methodist church, Satupaitea, Samoa c. 1908.jpg|Methodist stone church, [[Satupa'itea]], c. 1908\nFile:Piula Cave Pool, Upolu island, Samoa.jpg|[[Piula Cave Pool]] by the sea below the chapel.\nFile:Samoan lali log drums at Piula Theological College.JPG|''Lali'', Samoan wooden log drums, each 2m long used to beat out sound and signal times.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Religion in Samoa]]\n*[[Architecture of Samoa]]\n*[[History of Samoa]]\n*[[German Samoa]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Samoa}}\n{{South Pacific Association of Theological Schools}}\n[[Category:Methodism in Samoa]]\n[[Category:Methodist seminaries and theological colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Samoa]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in Samoa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Atua (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piula_Theological_College"}
{"title_page": "Pindeshwor Vidyapeeth", "text_new": "{{coord|26.815478|N|87.295643|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name =Pindeshwor Vidyapeeth\n|image_name =\n|image_size =\n|caption = Campus Building at Jaitar\n|established = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|p=y|1951|12|12}}\n|type = [[Public university|Public]] [[Coeducational]]\n|parent      = [[Nepal Sanskrit University]]\n|endowment =\n|chancellor =  \n|vice_chancellor = \n|chairman =\n|head_label= [[Principal (academia)|Principal]]\n|head =    Prof. Dr. Chandramani Nepal\n|faculty = [[Sanskrit]]\n|city =[[Dharan, Nepal|Dharan]]\n|country =[[Nepal]]\n|campus = 31.2404 acars\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Pindeshwor Vidyapeeth''' is one of the affiliated government Sanskrit colleges of Nepal Sanskrit University<ref>{{cite web|title=Affiliated Campuses and Vidhyapeeth|url=http://nsu.edu.np/site/?p=1109|website=Nepal Sanskrit University}}</ref> at Dharan  Sub-Municipality in [[Sunsari District]] of [[Nepal]]. This campus offers Uttarmadhyama (Intermediate) as well as Shastri (Bachelor) levels of study.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radhadamodar Sanskrit Vidhyapeeth|url=http://edusanjal.com/college/radhadamodar-sanskrit-vidyapeeth|website=edusanjal}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[http://nsu.edu.np/ Nepal Sanskrit University]\n{{Nepali universities}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coord|26.815478|N|87.295643|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name =Pindeshwor Vidyapeeth\n|image_name =\n|image_size =\n|caption = Campus Building at Jaitar\n|established = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|p=y|1951|12|12}}\n|type = [[Public university|Public]] [[Coeducational]]\n|parent      = [[Nepal Sanskrit University]]\n|endowment =\n|chancellor =  \n|vice_chancellor = \n|chairman =\n|head_label= [[Principal (academia)|Principal]]\n|head =    Prof. Dr. Chandramani Nepal\n|faculty = [[Sanskrit]]\n|city =[[Dharan, Nepal|Dharan]]\n|country =[[Nepal]]\n|campus = 31.2404 acars\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Pindeshwor Vidyapeeth''' is one of the affiliated government Sanskrit colleges of Nepal Sanskrit University<ref>{{cite web|title=Affiliated Campuses and Vidhyapeeth|url=http://nsu.edu.np/site/?p=1109|website=Nepal Sanskrit University}}</ref>at Dharan  Sub-Municipality in [[Sunsari District]] of [[Nepal]]. This campus offers Uttarmadhyama (Intermediate) as well as Shastri (Bachelor) levels of study.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radhadamodar Sanskrit Vidhyapeeth|url=http://edusanjal.com/college/radhadamodar-sanskrit-vidyapeeth|website=edusanjal}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[http://nsu.edu.np/ Nepal Sanskrit University]\n{{Nepali universities}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Nepal]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pindeshwor_Vidyapeeth"}
{"title_page": "Pilot University of Colombia", "text_new": "{{short description|Private coeducational research university in Colombia}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox university \n|name           = Pilot University of Colombia\n|native_name    = Universidad Piloto de Colombia\n|latin_name     =\n|image          = [[Image:Pilot University of Colombia.png|150px|Shield of Universidad Piloto de Colombia]]\n|motto          = Un espacio para la evoluci\u00f3n\n|motto_lang     = Spanish\n|mottoeng       = A space for evolution\n|established    = 1962\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]] \n|endowment      = \n|principal      = \n|students       =\n|undergrad      =  \n|postgrad       = \n|staff          = \n|city           = [[Bogot\u00e1]] \n|state          = [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]] \n|country        = [[Colombia]]\n|address        = Cra. 9 #45A-44\n|campus         =\n|free_label     =  \n|free           = \n|nickname       =UNIPILOTO \n|mascot         =  \n|website        = [http://www.unipiloto.edu.co/ www.unipiloto.edu.co]\n|logo           =\n|footnotes      =\n}}\n\nThe '''Universidad Piloto de Colombia''', is a private, national, coeducational research university, located primarily in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]. It offers academic programs in undergraduate, specializations, masters and doctorates. Its president is Patricia Piedrah\u00edta Castillo.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1962, a group of [[architecture]] students of the University of America (''Universidad de Am\u00e9rica''), showed their nonconformity before the mechanisms of education and academic formation established in the educational system of the University. The disagreement was that the architectural models taught were for european geography, and therefore, it was difficult to apply to the colombian geographical structure.\n\nAs a result of this, a student movement was created with the aim of reforming said system and restructuring it through an institution that responded to the needs of the young students. By August of the same year, a large number of students formed by work teams and under legal, economic and human management responsibilities, were installed in the National Park Theater temporarily, headed by students of higher semesters.\n\nA group of senators of the Republic, among which include doctors Alfonso Palacio Rudas and Ra\u00fal V\u00e1squez V\u00e9lez, decided to participate in the magnificent idea and provided the students and parents with the Elliptical Hall of the National Capitol, so that they would gather, discuss and approve the statutes on September 14, 1962 and give rise to the university, which was named ''Corporaci\u00f3n Universidad Piloto de Colombia''.\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:PILOTO APR.jpg|thumb|140px|Photo of the APR building at the Bogot\u00e1 campus]]\n\n===Bogot\u00e1 campus===\nThe university has 12 buildings made up of administrative headquarters, headquarters for postgraduate degrees, faculties, halls and laboratories for [[architecture]], [[engineering]] and [[psychology]]. The best-known buildings are called \"''Alfonso Palacio Rudas''\" (\"APR\"), building \"''Fundadores''\" (\"F\"), and building \"''Jos\u00e9 Alberto Alvarado''\" (\"G\"), characterized by its modern infrastructure, composed of crystalline material and concrete. It has 15 undergraduate programs.\n\n===Girardot campus===\nThe university also has a headquarters located in [[Girardot, Cundinamarca|Girardot]], Colombia, consisting of 4 buildings, located in an area of 2,144.83 square meters.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|4|37|56|N|74|3|55|W|display=title}}\n{{Universities in Colombia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Universidad Piloto de Colombia}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Private coeducational research university in Colombia}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox University \n|name           = Pilot University of Colombia\n|native_name    = Universidad Piloto de Colombia\n|latin_name     =\n|image          = [[Image:Pilot University of Colombia.png|150px|Shield of Universidad Piloto de Colombia]]\n|motto          = Un espacio para la evoluci\u00f3n\n|motto_lang     = Spanish\n|mottoeng       = A space for evolution\n|established    = 1962\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]] \n|endowment      = \n|principal      = \n|students       =\n|undergrad      =  \n|postgrad       = \n|staff          = \n|city           = [[Bogot\u00e1]] \n|state          = [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]] \n|country        = [[Colombia]]\n|address        = Cra. 9 #45A-44\n|campus         =\n|free_label     =  \n|free           = \n|nickname       =UNIPILOTO \n|mascot         =  \n|website        = [http://www.unipiloto.edu.co/ www.unipiloto.edu.co]\n|logo           =\n|footnotes      =\n}}\n\nThe '''Universidad Piloto de Colombia''', is a private, national, coeducational research university, located primarily in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]. It offers academic programs in undergraduate, specializations, masters and doctorates. Its president is Patricia Piedrah\u00edta Castillo.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1962, a group of [[architecture]] students of the University of America (''Universidad de Am\u00e9rica''), showed their nonconformity before the mechanisms of education and academic formation established in the educational system of the University. The disagreement was that the architectural models taught were for european geography, and therefore, it was difficult to apply to the colombian geographical structure.\n\nAs a result of this, a student movement was created with the aim of reforming said system and restructuring it through an institution that responded to the needs of the young students. By August of the same year, a large number of students formed by work teams and under legal, economic and human management responsibilities, were installed in the National Park Theater temporarily, headed by students of higher semesters.\n\nA group of senators of the Republic, among which include doctors Alfonso Palacio Rudas and Ra\u00fal V\u00e1squez V\u00e9lez, decided to participate in the magnificent idea and provided the students and parents with the Elliptical Hall of the National Capitol, so that they would gather, discuss and approve the statutes on September 14, 1962 and give rise to the university, which was named ''Corporaci\u00f3n Universidad Piloto de Colombia''.\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:PILOTO APR.jpg|thumb|140px|Photo of the APR building at the Bogot\u00e1 campus]]\n===Bogot\u00e1 campus===\nThe university has 12 buildings made up of administrative headquarters, headquarters for postgraduate degrees, faculties, halls and laboratories for [[architecture]], [[engineering]] and [[psychology]]. The best-known buildings are called \"''Alfonso Palacio Rudas''\" (\"APR\"), building \"''Fundadores''\" (\"F\"), and building \"''Jos\u00e9 Alberto Alvarado''\" (\"G\"), characterized by its modern infrastructure, composed of crystalline material and concrete. It has 15 undergraduate programs.\n\n===Girardot campus===\nThe university also has a headquarters located in [[Girardot, Cundinamarca|Girardot]], Colombia, consisting of 4 buildings, located in an area of 2,144.83 square meters.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|4|37|56|N|74|3|55|W|display=title}}\n{{Universities in Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Universidad Piloto de Colombia}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pilot_University_of_Colombia"}
{"title_page": "Pibulsongkram Rajabhat University", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n'''Pibulsongkram Rajabhat University (PSRU.)''' is a [[university]] in [[Phitsanulok Province]], [[Thailand]].\n\n==History==\nThe university was first established in 1926 as a teacher training school under the Royal Thai government's Primary School Act of 1921. King [[Rama VII]] bestowed the name '''Phitsanuwittayayon School''' and attended the opening on 7 January 1926, accompanied by Queen [[Ramphaiphanni]]. The school offered two years of training to Thai students who desired to become teachers in government schools.\n\nA separate women's teacher training institution opened in 1933, and in 1956 both were combined to create '''Pibulsongkram Teachers College''', named for then Prime Minister Field Marshal [[Plaek Phibunsongkhram]]. The teachers college began offering a bachelor of education degree in 1976. In 1981 it moved from its original sites on the [[Nan River]] to a new campus outside the city in Thung Thalaykaew.\n\nThe Education Act of 1984 allowed Pibulsongkram to offer degrees in other fields than education. On 14 February 1992 King [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] (Rama IX) bestowed the new name of [[Rajabhat University system|Rajabhat Institute]] Pibulsongkram. The institute was upgraded to a university on 14 June 2004 when the king gave his approval to the 2004 Rajabhat University Act.\n\n==Faculties==\nThe university offers degrees in six faculties: education, humanities and social science, management, industrial technology, science and technology, and agricultural technology.\n* Faculty of Education \n* Faculty of Management Science \n* Faculty of Science and Technology \n* Faculty of Food and Agricultural Technology\n* Faculty of Industrial Technology \n* Faculty of Humanities and Social Science \n* College of Local Management and Development \n* College of Nursing\n* Graduate School\n\n==Partner Institution==\n===Malaysia===\n*[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.psru.ac.th/en/ Official site]\n\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|16|49|41|N|100|12|37|E|region:TH-65_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1921]]\n[[Category:Phitsanulok]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Phitsanulok Province]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Siam]]\n\n\n{{Thailand-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=September 2015}}\n'''Pibulsongkram Rajabhat University (PSRU.)''' is a [[university]] in [[Phitsanulok Province]], [[Thailand]].\n\n==History==\nThe university was first established in 1926 as a teacher training school under the Royal Thai government's Primary School Act of 1921. King [[Rama VII]] bestowed the name '''Phitsanuwittayayon School''' and attended the opening on 7 January 1926, accompanied by Queen [[Ramphaiphanni]]. The school offered two years of training to Thai students who desired to become teachers in government schools.\n\nA separate women's teacher training institution opened in 1933, and in 1956 both were combined to create '''Pibulsongkram Teachers College''', named for then Prime Minister Field Marshal [[Plaek Phibunsongkhram]]. The teachers college began offering a bachelor of education degree in 1976. In 1981 it moved from its original sites on the [[Nan River]] to a new campus outside the city in Thung Thalaykaew.\n\nThe Education Act of 1984 allowed Pibulsongkram to offer degrees in other fields than education. On 14 February 1992 King [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] (Rama IX) bestowed the new name of [[Rajabhat University system|Rajabhat Institute]] Pibulsongkram. The institute was upgraded to a university on 14 June 2004 when the king gave his approval to the 2004 Rajabhat University Act.\n\n==Faculties==\nThe university offers degrees in six faculties: education, humanities and social science, management, industrial technology, science and technology, and agricultural technology.\n* Faculty of Education \n* Faculty of Management Science \n* Faculty of Science and Technology \n* Faculty of Food and Agricultural Technology\n* Faculty of Industrial Technology \n* Faculty of Humanities and Social Science \n* College of Local Management and Development \n* College of Nursing\n* Graduate School\n\n==Partner Institution==\n===Malaysia===\n*[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.psru.ac.th/en/ Official site]\n\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|16|49|41|N|100|12|37|E|region:TH-65_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1921]]\n[[Category:Phitsanulok]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Phitsanulok Province]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Siam]]\n\n\n{{Thailand-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pibulsongkram_Rajabhat_University"}
{"title_page": "Mark Davis (American football)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Davis\n| image              = Mark Davis (American football).jpg\n| image_upright      =\n| image_size         = \n| alt         =\n| caption     = Davis in 2017\n| birth_date = {{Birth based on age as of date|56|2011|10|9}}\n| birth_name         = Mark Clark Davis\n| birth_place = [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater = [[California State University, Chico]]\n| occupation = Businessman and sports franchise owner\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for = Principal owner of the [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n| networth = $500&nbsp;million<br/>(October 2015)\n| nationality = American\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = [[Al Davis]]<br>Carol Davis\n| website            =\n\n}}\n\n'''Mark Clark Davis''' (born 1954 or 1955)<ref name=tafur>{{cite news|last=Tafur |first=Vic |title=Davis family will retain ownership of Raiders |date=October 9, 2011 |page=B-9 |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]] |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/10/08/SPLP1LEMCC.DTL |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62JqrJEWp?url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2011%2F10%2F08%2FSPLP1LEMCC.DTL |archivedate=October 10, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is an American businessman, sellout to Las Vegas casino scumbags, and sports franchise owner. He is the principal owner and managing general partner of the [[Las Vegas Raiders]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Davis family will keep ownership of Raiders, executive says|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d822f1af5/article/davis-family-will-keep-ownership-of-raiders-executive-says|publisher=National Football League|date=October 8, 2011|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Poole |first=Monte |title=Monte Poole: Did Mark Davis make the call on Hue Jackson's firing? |date=January 10, 2012 |publisher=[[Bay Area News Group]] |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_19712704 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64ayV1VL0?url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_19712704 |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Williamson |first=Bill |title=Mark Davis knows his role in Oakland |date=January 6, 2012 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/38300/mark-davis-knows-his-role-in-oakland |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64ayhAIMn?url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/38300/mark-davis-knows-his-role-in-oakland |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> {{As of|October 2015}}, Davis has an estimated $500&nbsp;million net worth.<ref>{{cite news|last=Knowlton|first=Emmett|title=Oakland Raiders owner is worth $500&nbsp;million and still uses a 2003 Nokia phone and drives a minivan|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/raiders-owner-mark-davis-worth-2015-10|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=October 2, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nDavis was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] to [[Al Davis|Al]] and Carol Davis.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/art-shell-and-mark-clark-davis/article_cb7f4d2f-6d2b-503a-83aa-3063fb9c8c75.html|title=Art Shell and Mark Clark Davis|last=Sapakoff|first=Gene|date=October 10, 2011|website=Post and Courier|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131053754/https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/art-shell-and-mark-clark-davis/article_cb7f4d2f-6d2b-503a-83aa-3063fb9c8c75.html|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> He was named after [[Mark W. Clark]], a US Army General.<ref name=\":0\" /> Davis is a graduate of [[California State University, Chico]].<ref name=\"tafur\" />\n\nPrior to owning the team, Davis was involved in the retail part of the Raiders' business where he helped develop the organization's Raider Image stores. He also spent time in the Raiders equipment department where he developed the muff-style hand warmer for football. In 1980, Davis represented Raiders player [[Cliff Branch]] in contract negotiations with the team which resulted in a deal that included an [[annuity]] (active until his death in 2019) and got Mark kicked out of his father's house for being too close to the players. He later lived with Branch when the team moved to Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keown|first=Tim|title=Just live up to your dad's name and solve the NFL's L.A. problem, baby!|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland|publisher=ESPN|date=October 14, 2014|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Professional sports==\n===Oakland / Las Vegas Raiders===\nDavis inherited the team after the death of his father, [[Al Davis]], in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |title=Prepping for Tuesday's Raiders media conference |date=January 9, 2012 |publisher=Comcast Sportsnet Bay Area |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Prepping-for-Tuesdays-Raiders-media-conf?blockID=627992&feedID=2801 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64b0SvkmT?url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Prepping-for-Tuesdays-Raiders-media-conf?blockID=627992&feedID=2801 |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Statement from Raiders owner Mark Davis |date=January 10, 2012 |publisher=Comcast Sportsnet Bay Area |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Statement-from-Raiders-owner-Mark-Davis-?blockID=628580&feedID=2539 |accessdate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120728184742/http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Statement-from-Raiders-owner-Mark-Davis-?blockID=628580&feedID=2539 |archivedate=July 28, 2012 }}</ref> Davis with his mother, Carol, owns a 47&nbsp;percent share of the Raiders, which is contractually structured to give them [[controlling interest]]. Davis has day-to-day control of the team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dickey |first=Glenn |title=Oakland Raiders in need of major front-office makeover |date=January 5, 2012 |newspaper=The San Francisco Examiner |url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/nfl/2012/01/oakland-raiders-need-major-front-office-makeover |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64b3hz10K?url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/nfl/2012/01/oakland-raiders-need-major-front-office-makeover |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDavis gained control of the team towards the end of the Raiders lease with the [[Oakland Coliseum]], a facility that dates back to 1965 and had multiple issues due to its age. It was also at the time the only facility that still housed both a [[Major League Baseball]] and NFL team, a major point of contention for both leagues. \n\n====Relocation to Las Vegas====\n{{Main|Oakland Raiders relocation to Las Vegas|Carson Stadium|Allegiant Stadium}}{{Off topic|date=May 2019}}<!-- Section needs to be shortened and summarized -->\n\nDavis put himself in charge of an effort to establish a new stadium for the Raiders, an issue that his father Al was never able to solve in his tenure as owner. He initially stated a desire to keep the Raiders in [[Oakland]] (preferably on the Coliseum site) or the immediate area. Due to the lack of a stadium plan, Davis began to communicate with representatives in other cities such as Los Angeles, California, [[San Antonio]], Texas and in the end [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2014/07/30/raiders-owner-confirms-talks-with-san-antonio/13362091/|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis admits meeting in San Antonio|agency=Associated Press|date=July 30, 2014|work=USA Today|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/84278/qa-with-raiders-owner-mark-davis|title=Q&A with Oakland Raiders owner Mark Davis \u2013 NFL Nation |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2015, Davis announced that the Raiders would pursue a shared stadium in [[Carson, California]], with [[Dean Spanos]] and the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-20150220-story.html#page=1|title=Chargers, Raiders will jointly pursue an NFL stadium in Carson|date=February 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> Davis cited the proposal as the result of years of talks with Oakland city officials that ultimately led nowhere. While the Chargers have historically been inter-divisional rivals, he recognized that Spanos was in a similar position with [[San Diego]] city officials and that their partnership could expedite the process of resolving the stadium issue for both franchises.<ref name=\"LA Times\" /> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that the team's relocation could result in the franchise \"being worth 150% of its current value\".<ref name=\"LA Times\" />\n\nOn February 23, 2015, while still involved in the Carson project, Mark Davis attended a secret meeting at the UNLV International Gaming Institute to look at Las Vegas [[sports betting]], its effect on pro sports, how it could effect a pro sports team in Vegas and how the Raiders and the NFL could possibly work in Las Vegas. At the time Las Vegas was seen as a long shot candidate for the Raiders. The meeting was set up by [[Napoleon McCallum]], former Raiders player and current [[Las Vegas Sands]] employee. In attendance was Davis and McCallum along with then [[UNLV]] president Don Snyder and Bo Bernhard, executive director of the International Gaming Institute. The meeting would not be known about until two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/23003330/nfl-how-two-las-vegas-dads-helped-raiders-get-comfortable-sports-betting?platform=amp|title=How the Raiders got comfortable with sports betting|publisher=ESPN|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2015, a new proposal for the Carson stadium was released, outlining several personalized touches for the shared tenants.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-renderings-carson-20150424-story.html|title=Chargers and Raiders overhaul design for potential L.A. stadium|date=April 23, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> These include stadium seating changing from navy blue to black depending on which team homefield, as well as a 120-foot tower on the concourse that would serve as a memorial for the late [[Al Davis]] for Raiders touchdowns or shoot simulated lightning for Chargers' touchdowns.<ref name=\"latimes.com\" /> The Carson stadium proposal also featured sprawling ground-level parking, rather than multi-story carparks, at the request of Davis who insisted that tailgating at a new stadium was a necessity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/mark-davis-carson-stadium-project-very-interesting-me|title=Mark Davis: Carson stadium project 'very interesting to me'|work=CSN Bay Area|accessdate=June 5, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609030101/http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/mark-davis-carson-stadium-project-very-interesting-me|archivedate=June 9, 2015}}</ref> Davis' and Spanos' proposal directly competed with and eventually lost to [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]]' owner [[Stan Kroenke]] and his [[SoFi Stadium|proposed stadium]] in [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-inglewood-20150322-column.html|title=Stan Kroenke ready to show NFL owners detailed Inglewood stadium plans|date=March 21, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Carson Stadium design was retained by Davis with the small additions of a roof and black covering instead of silver in a stadium proposal with [[Sheldon Adelson]]'s [[Las Vegas Sands Corporation]] to interests in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].\n\nUntil after the Carson vote Davis was also actively working towards a resolution in Oakland.<ref name=\"Rapp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000431256/article/mark-davis-were-trying-everything-to-get-oakland-stadium-deal|title=Mark Davis: We're trying everything to get Oakland stadium deal|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> In an interview, he said \"we are trying everything possible to get something done in Oakland right on the same exact site we're on right now\".<ref name=\"Rapp\" /> The Oakland stadium proposal called for a smaller 55,000-seat stadium at the current site, with space for commercial development and renovations for the existing [[Oakland Coliseum Station|BART Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc7news.com/sports/coliseum-city-planners-not-deterred-by-carsons-vote/677450/|title=Oakland Coliseum City planners not deterred by Carson's vote|work=ABC7 San Francisco|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a dispute over rent in Oakland where the city raised the rent on the team after the Carson plan failed and a lack of what Davis saw as a credible plan from Oakland, Mark Davis began discussions with Las Vegas. He initially teamed up with Sheldon Adelson to get a stadium in Las Vegas.\n\nDuring Davis' meeting with Adelson, he also visited the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] (UNLV), which included a contingent consisting of the university's president [[Len Jessup]], former university president Donald Snyder, [[Steve Wynn]], and former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) owner [[Lorenzo Fertitta]]. The stadium is being proposed to replace [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] and would serve as the home of both the Raiders and the [[UNLV Rebels football|UNLV Rebels]] [[college football]] program. A relocation to Las Vegas would be a long-term proposal, as Sam Boyd Stadium is undersized for the NFL and there are no other professional-caliber stadiums in [[Nevada]]. Raiders officials were also in Las Vegas to tour locations in the valley for a potential new home; they were also on the 42-acre site of the proposed stadium to ask questions about the site.\n\nInterviewed by sports columnist Tim Kawakami of the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'', Davis said that he had a \"great\" visit in the city he described it as interesting. Davis also said that Las Vegas was a global city and that \"it's absolutely an NFL city,\" as well as saying that \"the Raider brand would do well\" and \"I think Las Vegas is coming along slowly\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Sands wants stadium for UNLV, possibly Raiders|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2016/01/28/ap-fbo-las-vegas-sands-stadium|agency=Associated Press|work=Sports Illustrated|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=March 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, when asked about Las Vegas, Davis said, \"I think the Raiders like the Las Vegas plan,\" and \"it's a very very very intriguing and exciting plan\", referring to the stadium plan in Las Vegas. Davis also met with [[List of Governors of Nevada|Nevada Governor]] [[Brian Sandoval]] about the stadium plan. On April 1, 2016, Davis toured Sam Boyd Stadium to evaluate whether UNLV could serve as a temporary home of the team and was with UNLV football coach Tony Sanchez, athletic director Tina Kunzer-Murphy, adviser Don Snyder and school president Len Jessup to further explore the possibility of the Raiders moving to Las Vegas.\n\nOn April 28, 2016, Davis said he wanted to move the Raiders to Las Vegas and pledged $500&nbsp;million toward the construction of a proposed $2.4&nbsp;billion domed stadium.<ref name=\"DavisPledgeVegas\">{{cite news|title=Raiders owner willing to give $20M toward Las Vegas stadium|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000656715/article/raiders-owner-willing-to-give-500m-toward-las-vegas-stadium|publisher=National Football League|agency=Associated Press|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Paul|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis says he wants to move team to Las Vegas |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15420427/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-says-wants-move-team-las-vegas|publisher=ESPN|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> \"Together we can turn the Silver State into the silver and black state,\" Davis said.<ref name=\"DavisPledgeVegas\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Oakland Raiders owner willing to spend $500&nbsp;million to move team to Vegas|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2016/04/28/oakland-raiders-owner-willing-to-spend-500-million-to-move-team-to-vegas.html|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|agency=Associated Press|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt a media conference in UNLV's Stan Fulton Building, Davis also said the club had \"made a commitment to Las Vegas at this point in time and that's where it stands.\" In an interview with [[ESPN]] after returning from a meeting for the [[2016 NFL draft]] he expanded upon reasons why Southern Nevada held a certain appeal over the [[East Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|East Bay]] of the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Oakland\u2013San Francisco Bay Area]], how he tried to make it work in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and why (as he told Sandoval) he hopes to turn Nevada into the \"Silver and Black State\"; he also spoke of the meeting saying, \"It was a positive, well-organized presentation that I believe was well-received\", and stating, \"It was a very positive step in finding the Raiders a home.\"\n\nOn May 20, 2016, [[New England Patriots]] owner [[Robert Kraft]] said he would support Davis and the Raiders move to Las Vegas, stating, \"I think it would be good for the NFL.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Knoblauch|first=Austin|title=Robert Kraft would support Raiders move to Las Vegas|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000664187/article/robert-kraft-would-support-raiders-move-to-las-vegas|publisher=National Football League|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\nIf the Raiders were to move to Las Vegas the only competition they would have is the [[Vegas Golden Knights]] of the [[National Hockey League]]. On August 11, 2016, Raiders officials met with Northern Nevada officials about the possibility of [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] being the site of a new training camp/practice facility and toured several sites including the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], Reno area high schools, and sports complexes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raiders relocation could include Reno training camp|last=Richardson|first=Seth|url=http://www.rgj.com/story/sports/2016/08/10/raiders-relocation-could-include-reno-training-camp/88547986|accessdate=September 24, 2016|work=[[Reno Gazette-Journal]]|date=August 11, 2016}}</ref> On August 25, 2016, the Raiders filed a trademark application for \"Las Vegas Raiders\" on the same day renderings of a new stadium (located west of [[Interstate 15]] at Las Vegas) were released to the public.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez|first=A.J.|title=Oakland Raiders file to trademark 'Las Vegas Raiders' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2016/08/25/raiders-las-vegas-trademark-relocation/89341228/|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2016, the Southern Nevada Tourism Infrastructure Committee unanimously voted to recommend and approve $750&nbsp;million for the Las Vegas stadium plan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stadium plan to lure Raiders to Las Vegas passes vote|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000703280/article/stadium-plan-to-lure-raiders-to-las-vegas-passes-vote|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2016, the [[Nevada Senate]] voted 16\u20135 to approve the funding bill for the Las Vegas stadium proposal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chereb|first1=Sandra|last2=Whaley|first2=Sean|title=Raiders stadium project for Las Vegas clears Nevada Senate in 16\u20135 vote|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/stadium/raiders-stadium-project-las-vegas-clears-nevada-senate-16-5-vote|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|date=October 11, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref> The [[Nevada Assembly]] voted 28\u201313 three days later to approve the bill to fund the new Las Vegas stadium proposal; two days later, Sandoval signed the funding bill into law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas stadium plan gains approval from Nevada Legislature|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000720822/article/las-vegas-stadium-plan-gains-approval-from-nevada-legislature|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=October 14, 2016|accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDavis told [[ESPN]] on October 15, 2016 that even if the Raiders are approved by the league to relocate to the [[Las Vegas metropolitan area]], the club would play the next two seasons at the [[Oakland Alameda Coliseum]] in 2017 and 2018, stating \"We want to bring a Super Bowl championship back to the Bay Area.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Gutierrez|first=Paul|title=Mark Davis: Raiders' Oakland plan unchanged even if Las Vegas deal OK'd|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17802673/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-reiterates-desire-play-coliseum-next-two-years-las-vegas-deal|publisher=ESPN|date=October 15, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> The team originally planned to play at a temporary facility in 2019 after its lease at the Coliseum expired, but they were able to get a two year extension by the Coliseum board in March of 2019, with the second year in 2020 tagged on as insurance in case Allegiant Stadium was not ready in time. Davis had also indicated a desire to play at least one preseason game in Las Vegas, at Sam Boyd Stadium, as early as the 2017 season, but this ultimately never came into fruition.\n\nOn October 17, 2016, Nevada Governor Brian Sandoval signed into law Senate Bill 1 and Assembly Bill 1 which approved a hotel room rate tax increase to accommodate $750&nbsp;million in public funding for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nevada governor signs bill to approve Las Vegas stadium plan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000722987/article/nevada-governor-signs-bill-to-approve-las-vegas-stadium-plan|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=October 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spousta|first=Tom|title=Gov. Brian Sandoval signs Raiders stadium bill \u2013 VIDEO|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/stadium/gov-brian-sandoval-signs-raiders-stadium-bill-video|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=October 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Raiders officially filed paperwork to relocate from Oakland, California, to Las Vegas, Nevada, on January 19, 2017. On January 30, 2017, it was announced that Adelson had dropped out of the stadium project, also withdrawing the Las Vegas Sands' proposed $650&nbsp;million contribution from the project.  Instead, the Raiders would increase their contribution from $500&nbsp;million to $1.15&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adelson no longer involved in Raiders' Las Vegas stadium plan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000781086/article/adelson-no-longer-involved-in-raiders-las-vegas-stadium-plan|publisher=National Football League|date=January 30, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> One day after Adelson's announcement, [[Goldman Sachs]] (the company behind the financing to the proposed Las Vegas stadium) announced its intent to withdraw from the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sources: Financial giant Goldman Sachs backs out of Raiders' stadium deal|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18594904/oakland-raiders-las-vegas-stadium-deal-loses-backing-goldman-sachs|publisher=ESPN|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2017, the Raiders revealed [[Bank of America]] would be replacing the Sheldon Adelson portion of the funding.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raiders secure financing for potential Las Vegas stadium|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000790903/article/raiders-secure-financing-for-potential-las-vegas-stadium|publisher=National Football League|date=March 7, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jon Mark Saraceno|title=Raiders' Las Vegas stadium gets boost from Bank of America|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/nfl-vegas/bank-america-bankroll-raiders-stadium-las-vegas|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=March 6, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref> On March 27, 2017, the National Football League officially approved the Raiders move from Oakland to Las Vegas in a 31\u20131 vote, ensuring them a new stadium in the process.\n\n====Management style====\nIn his short ownership of the Raiders, Davis has focused on the business aspects of the team while leaving football matters in the hands of general manager [[Reggie McKenzie (linebacker)|Reggie McKenzie]]. This form of management is in stark contrast to his father, who was well known as one of the most hands-on owners in professional sports. Al Davis became general manager of the Raiders in 1966 after returning from a short stint as AFL commissioner, a post he kept after becoming principal owner in 1972. He exercised close control over both business and football matters until his death.\n\nIn 2013, Davis fired the Raiders public relations director because of a ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' article that was critical of Davis' father. Davis stated that the director's replacement needed to understand the importance of his father's legacy and actively protect it.<ref name=\"2013Davis\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9357655/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-zak-gilbert-exit-no-shot-reggie-mckenzie|title=Raiders' Mark Davis: 'Reggie's fine'|date=June 9, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===On domestic violence in the NFL===\nDavis spoke out publicly on the issue of [[National Football League controversies#Domestic violence|domestic violence in the NFL]], following [[San Francisco 49ers]] defensive lineman [[Ray McDonald]]'s arrest on August 31, 2014.<ref name=\"WA Post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/09/18/raiders-owner-mark-davis-has-an-idea-for-solving-nfls-domestic-violence-crisis/|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis says he can solve the NFL's domestic-violence crisis|author=Cindy Boren|date=September 18, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> Davis disagreed with [[Jed York]]'s decision to keep McDonald on the active roster, proposing that the league should suspend any player arrested with pay while \"the investigation moves forward\"<ref name=\"WA Post\" /> This was the first proposal of this kind following the [[Ray Rice#Personal life|Ray Rice assault video]] surfacing, that specifically called for an immediate suspension of players rather than leaving the decision to suspend up to the respective franchises themselves. In March 2015, Davis again went public on the issue of domestic violence, shutting down rumors that the Raiders' started negotiations with [[Greg Hardy#Domestic abuse|Greg Hardy]], who was convicted on domestic abuse charges earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/mark-davis-is-not-happy-raiders-used-as-greg-hardy-s-leverage-195946487.html|title=Mark Davis is not happy Raiders used as Greg Hardy's leverage|date=March 13, 2015|work=Yahoo Sports|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> The Raiders' organization has traditionally been vocal about domestic violence issues, with direct involvement with the [[Fred Biletnikoff#Personal life|Tracey Biletnikoff Foundation]], created by Hall of Famer [[Fred Biletnikoff]] to support community substance abuse treatment and domestic violence programs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/may/07/sports/sp-27521|title=Former Raider Star Biletnikoff Honors Deceased Daughter|last=Peterson|first=Anne M.|date=May 7, 2000|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===On social justice and player protests===\nDavis has spoken out publicly on the controversial [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|National Anthem protests]] in the NFL where players kneel during the playing of the pre-game National Anthem to protest social injustice and police brutality on African Americans. Davis originally preferred his players to stand but after comments made by President [[Donald Trump]] calling protesting players \"Sons of Bitches\" and saying they should be fired for kneeling Davis changed his stance in a public statement the following weekend stating \"About a year ago before our Tennessee game I met with [[Derek Carr]] and [[Khalil Mack]] to ask their permission to have [[Tommie Smith]] light the torch for my father before the game in Mexico City,\" Davis told ESPN's Paul Gutierrez. \"I explained to them I was asking their permission because I had previously told them that I would prefer that they not protest while in Raiders uniform. And should they have something to say once their uniform was off, I might go up there with them. Over the last year, though,\" Davis continued, \"the streets have gotten hot and there has been a lot of static in the air and recently fuel has been added to the fire. I can no longer ask our team not to say something while they are in a Raider uniform. The only thing I can ask them to do is do it with class. Do it with pride. Not only do we have to tell people there is something wrong, we have to come up with answers. That's the challenge that's in front of us as Americans and as human beings.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2017/9/24/16357598/mark-davis-i-can-no-longer-ask-our-team-to-not-say-something-while-they-are-in-a-raiders-uniform|title=Mark Davis: \u2018I can no longer ask our team to not say something while they are in a Raider uniform\u2019|work=Silver And Black Pride|access-date=24 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Davis abstained from an NFL owner resolution on the anthem protests that called for players to stand or stay in the locker room until after the anthem is played or face a team fine for kneeling, locking arms or raising their fist. Davis abstained along with [[San Francisco 49ers]] owner [[Jed York]] after speaking out on social justice issues to the other owners.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2018/5/24/17390248/raiders-owner-mark-davis-abstained-owner-vote-on-anthem-resolution-spoke-up-social-justice-issues|title=Mark Davis abstained from owner vote on anthem resolution, spoke up on social justice issues|work=Silver And Black Pride|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/05/24/raiders-mark-davis-confirms-he-abstained-from-anthem-vote/|title=Raiders\u2019 Mark Davis confirms he abstained from anthem vote|date=May 24, 2018|work=The Mercury News|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDavis says he is a food connoisseur and has said that his favorite restaurants include Dan Tana's in Los Angeles, California, Joe's Stone Crab in Miami Beach, Florida, and [[P.F. Chang's]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The TK Show \u2013 Mark Davis \u2013 EP04A|url = https://soundcloud.com/mercurynews/tkshow-mark-davis-ep04a|website = SoundCloud|accessdate = 9 April 2015}}</ref> Davis is known for his signature [[bowl cut|bowl haircut]] and for driving a 1997 [[Dodge Caravan]] SE which is outfitted with a bubble-top Mark III conversion kit as well as a VHS player mounted to the roof.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wickersham |first1=Seth |last2=Van Natta Jr.|first2=Don |title=Sin City Or Bust |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/sin-city-bust/story?id=46773399 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=April 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Keown |first1=Tim |title=Just live up to your dad's name and solve the NFL's L.A. problem, baby! |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> Davis donated $10,000 to the Gridiron [[Political action committee|PAC]] between 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis|title=Get to know Mark Davis, the Oakland Raiders' owner|date=July 16, 2018|website=Sports Illustrated|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131061521/https://www.si.com/nfl/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last=Kawakami |first=Tim |title=Oakland Raiders owner Mark Davis makes good first impression |date=January 11, 2012 |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_19712614 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64cb7XWcI?url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_19712614 |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland/ Profile piece on Mark Davis done in 2014] from [[ESPN]]\n\n{{Las Vegas Raiders}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders owner navbox}}\n{{NFLOwners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Mark}}\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders owners]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Raiders owners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Davis\n| image              = Mark Davis (American football).jpg\n| image_upright      =\n| image_size         = \n| alt         =\n| caption     = Davis in 2017\n| birth_date = {{Birth based on age as of date|56|2011|10|9}}\n| birth_name         = Mark Clark Davis\n| birth_place = [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater = [[California State University, Chico]]\n| occupation = Businessman and sports franchise owner\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for = Principal owner of the [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n| networth = $500&nbsp;million<br/>(October 2015)\n| nationality = American\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = [[Al Davis]]<br>Carol Davis\n| website            =\n\n}}\n\n'''Mark Clark Davis''' (born 1954 or 1955)<ref name=tafur>{{cite news|last=Tafur |first=Vic |title=Davis family will retain ownership of Raiders |date=October 9, 2011 |page=B-9 |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]] |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/10/08/SPLP1LEMCC.DTL |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62JqrJEWp?url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2011%2F10%2F08%2FSPLP1LEMCC.DTL |archivedate=October 10, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is an American businessman and sports franchise owner. He is the principal owner and managing general partner of the [[Las Vegas Raiders]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Davis family will keep ownership of Raiders, executive says|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d822f1af5/article/davis-family-will-keep-ownership-of-raiders-executive-says|publisher=National Football League|date=October 8, 2011|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Poole |first=Monte |title=Monte Poole: Did Mark Davis make the call on Hue Jackson's firing? |date=January 10, 2012 |publisher=[[Bay Area News Group]] |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_19712704 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64ayV1VL0?url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_19712704 |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Williamson |first=Bill |title=Mark Davis knows his role in Oakland |date=January 6, 2012 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/38300/mark-davis-knows-his-role-in-oakland |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64ayhAIMn?url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/38300/mark-davis-knows-his-role-in-oakland |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> {{As of|October 2015}}, Davis has an estimated $500&nbsp;million net worth.<ref>{{cite news|last=Knowlton|first=Emmett|title=Oakland Raiders owner is worth $500&nbsp;million and still uses a 2003 Nokia phone and drives a minivan|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/raiders-owner-mark-davis-worth-2015-10|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=October 2, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nDavis was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] to [[Al Davis|Al]] and Carol Davis.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/art-shell-and-mark-clark-davis/article_cb7f4d2f-6d2b-503a-83aa-3063fb9c8c75.html|title=Art Shell and Mark Clark Davis|last=Sapakoff|first=Gene|date=October 10, 2011|website=Post and Courier|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131053754/https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/art-shell-and-mark-clark-davis/article_cb7f4d2f-6d2b-503a-83aa-3063fb9c8c75.html|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> He was named after [[Mark W. Clark]], a US Army General.<ref name=\":0\" /> Davis is a graduate of [[California State University, Chico]].<ref name=\"tafur\" />\n\nPrior to owning the team, Davis was involved in the retail part of the Raiders' business where he helped develop the organization's Raider Image stores. He also spent time in the Raiders equipment department where he developed the muff-style hand warmer for football. In 1980, Davis represented Raiders player [[Cliff Branch]] in contract negotiations with the team which resulted in a deal that included an [[annuity]] (active until his death in 2019) and got Mark kicked out of his father's house for being too close to the players. He later lived with Branch when the team moved to Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keown|first=Tim|title=Just live up to your dad's name and solve the NFL's L.A. problem, baby!|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland|publisher=ESPN|date=October 14, 2014|accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Professional sports==\n===Oakland / Las Vegas Raiders===\nDavis inherited the team after the death of his father, [[Al Davis]], in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |title=Prepping for Tuesday's Raiders media conference |date=January 9, 2012 |publisher=Comcast Sportsnet Bay Area |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Prepping-for-Tuesdays-Raiders-media-conf?blockID=627992&feedID=2801 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64b0SvkmT?url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Prepping-for-Tuesdays-Raiders-media-conf?blockID=627992&feedID=2801 |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Statement from Raiders owner Mark Davis |date=January 10, 2012 |publisher=Comcast Sportsnet Bay Area |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Statement-from-Raiders-owner-Mark-Davis-?blockID=628580&feedID=2539 |accessdate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120728184742/http://www.csnbayarea.com/blog/raiders-talk/post/Statement-from-Raiders-owner-Mark-Davis-?blockID=628580&feedID=2539 |archivedate=July 28, 2012 }}</ref> Davis with his mother, Carol, owns a 47&nbsp;percent share of the Raiders, which is contractually structured to give them [[controlling interest]]. Davis has day-to-day control of the team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dickey |first=Glenn |title=Oakland Raiders in need of major front-office makeover |date=January 5, 2012 |newspaper=The San Francisco Examiner |url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/nfl/2012/01/oakland-raiders-need-major-front-office-makeover |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64b3hz10K?url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/nfl/2012/01/oakland-raiders-need-major-front-office-makeover |archivedate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDavis gained control of the team towards the end of the Raiders lease with the [[Oakland Coliseum]], a facility that dates back to 1965 and had multiple issues due to its age. It was also at the time the only facility that still housed both a [[Major League Baseball]] and NFL team, a major point of contention for both leagues. \n\n====Relocation to Las Vegas====\n{{Main|Oakland Raiders relocation to Las Vegas|Carson Stadium|Allegiant Stadium}}{{Off topic|date=May 2019}}<!-- Section needs to be shortened and summarized -->\n\nDavis put himself in charge of an effort to establish a new stadium for the Raiders, an issue that his father Al was never able to solve in his tenure as owner. He initially stated a desire to keep the Raiders in [[Oakland]] (preferably on the Coliseum site) or the immediate area. Due to the lack of a stadium plan, Davis began to communicate with representatives in other cities such as Los Angeles, California, [[San Antonio]], Texas and in the end [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2014/07/30/raiders-owner-confirms-talks-with-san-antonio/13362091/|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis admits meeting in San Antonio|agency=Associated Press|date=July 30, 2014|work=USA Today|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/84278/qa-with-raiders-owner-mark-davis|title=Q&A with Oakland Raiders owner Mark Davis \u2013 NFL Nation |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2015, Davis announced that the Raiders would pursue a shared stadium in [[Carson, California]], with [[Dean Spanos]] and the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-20150220-story.html#page=1|title=Chargers, Raiders will jointly pursue an NFL stadium in Carson|date=February 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> Davis cited the proposal as the result of years of talks with Oakland city officials that ultimately led nowhere. While the Chargers have historically been inter-divisional rivals, he recognized that Spanos was in a similar position with [[San Diego]] city officials and that their partnership could expedite the process of resolving the stadium issue for both franchises.<ref name=\"LA Times\" /> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that the team's relocation could result in the franchise \"being worth 150% of its current value\".<ref name=\"LA Times\" />\n\nOn February 23, 2015, while still involved in the Carson project, Mark Davis attended a secret meeting at the UNLV International Gaming Institute to look at Las Vegas [[sports betting]], its effect on pro sports, how it could effect a pro sports team in Vegas and how the Raiders and the NFL could possibly work in Las Vegas. At the time Las Vegas was seen as a long shot candidate for the Raiders. The meeting was set up by [[Napoleon McCallum]], former Raiders player and current [[Las Vegas Sands]] employee. In attendance was Davis and McCallum along with then [[UNLV]] president Don Snyder and Bo Bernhard, executive director of the International Gaming Institute. The meeting would not be known about until two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/23003330/nfl-how-two-las-vegas-dads-helped-raiders-get-comfortable-sports-betting?platform=amp|title=How the Raiders got comfortable with sports betting|publisher=ESPN|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2015, a new proposal for the Carson stadium was released, outlining several personalized touches for the shared tenants.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-renderings-carson-20150424-story.html|title=Chargers and Raiders overhaul design for potential L.A. stadium|date=April 23, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> These include stadium seating changing from navy blue to black depending on which team homefield, as well as a 120-foot tower on the concourse that would serve as a memorial for the late [[Al Davis]] for Raiders touchdowns or shoot simulated lightning for Chargers' touchdowns.<ref name=\"latimes.com\" /> The Carson stadium proposal also featured sprawling ground-level parking, rather than multi-story carparks, at the request of Davis who insisted that tailgating at a new stadium was a necessity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/mark-davis-carson-stadium-project-very-interesting-me|title=Mark Davis: Carson stadium project 'very interesting to me'|work=CSN Bay Area|accessdate=June 5, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609030101/http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/mark-davis-carson-stadium-project-very-interesting-me|archivedate=June 9, 2015}}</ref> Davis' and Spanos' proposal directly competed with and eventually lost to [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]]' owner [[Stan Kroenke]] and his [[SoFi Stadium|proposed stadium]] in [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-nfl-stadium-inglewood-20150322-column.html|title=Stan Kroenke ready to show NFL owners detailed Inglewood stadium plans|date=March 21, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Carson Stadium design was retained by Davis with the small additions of a roof and black covering instead of silver in a stadium proposal with [[Sheldon Adelson]]'s [[Las Vegas Sands Corporation]] to interests in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].\n\nUntil after the Carson vote Davis was also actively working towards a resolution in Oakland.<ref name=\"Rapp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000431256/article/mark-davis-were-trying-everything-to-get-oakland-stadium-deal|title=Mark Davis: We're trying everything to get Oakland stadium deal|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> In an interview, he said \"we are trying everything possible to get something done in Oakland right on the same exact site we're on right now\".<ref name=\"Rapp\" /> The Oakland stadium proposal called for a smaller 55,000-seat stadium at the current site, with space for commercial development and renovations for the existing [[Oakland Coliseum Station|BART Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc7news.com/sports/coliseum-city-planners-not-deterred-by-carsons-vote/677450/|title=Oakland Coliseum City planners not deterred by Carson's vote|work=ABC7 San Francisco|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a dispute over rent in Oakland where the city raised the rent on the team after the Carson plan failed and a lack of what Davis saw as a credible plan from Oakland, Mark Davis began discussions with Las Vegas. He initially teamed up with Sheldon Adelson to get a stadium in Las Vegas.\n\nDuring Davis' meeting with Adelson, he also visited the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] (UNLV), which included a contingent consisting of the university's president [[Len Jessup]], former university president Donald Snyder, [[Steve Wynn]], and former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) owner [[Lorenzo Fertitta]]. The stadium is being proposed to replace [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] and would serve as the home of both the Raiders and the [[UNLV Rebels football|UNLV Rebels]] [[college football]] program. A relocation to Las Vegas would be a long-term proposal, as Sam Boyd Stadium is undersized for the NFL and there are no other professional-caliber stadiums in [[Nevada]]. Raiders officials were also in Las Vegas to tour locations in the valley for a potential new home; they were also on the 42-acre site of the proposed stadium to ask questions about the site.\n\nInterviewed by sports columnist Tim Kawakami of the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'', Davis said that he had a \"great\" visit in the city he described it as interesting. Davis also said that Las Vegas was a global city and that \"it's absolutely an NFL city,\" as well as saying that \"the Raider brand would do well\" and \"I think Las Vegas is coming along slowly\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Sands wants stadium for UNLV, possibly Raiders|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2016/01/28/ap-fbo-las-vegas-sands-stadium|agency=Associated Press|work=Sports Illustrated|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=March 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, when asked about Las Vegas, Davis said, \"I think the Raiders like the Las Vegas plan,\" and \"it's a very very very intriguing and exciting plan\", referring to the stadium plan in Las Vegas. Davis also met with [[List of Governors of Nevada|Nevada Governor]] [[Brian Sandoval]] about the stadium plan. On April 1, 2016, Davis toured Sam Boyd Stadium to evaluate whether UNLV could serve as a temporary home of the team and was with UNLV football coach Tony Sanchez, athletic director Tina Kunzer-Murphy, adviser Don Snyder and school president Len Jessup to further explore the possibility of the Raiders moving to Las Vegas.\n\nOn April 28, 2016, Davis said he wanted to move the Raiders to Las Vegas and pledged $500&nbsp;million toward the construction of a proposed $2.4&nbsp;billion domed stadium.<ref name=\"DavisPledgeVegas\">{{cite news|title=Raiders owner willing to give $20M toward Las Vegas stadium|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000656715/article/raiders-owner-willing-to-give-500m-toward-las-vegas-stadium|publisher=National Football League|agency=Associated Press|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Paul|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis says he wants to move team to Las Vegas |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15420427/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-says-wants-move-team-las-vegas|publisher=ESPN|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> \"Together we can turn the Silver State into the silver and black state,\" Davis said.<ref name=\"DavisPledgeVegas\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Oakland Raiders owner willing to spend $500&nbsp;million to move team to Vegas|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2016/04/28/oakland-raiders-owner-willing-to-spend-500-million-to-move-team-to-vegas.html|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|agency=Associated Press|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt a media conference in UNLV's Stan Fulton Building, Davis also said the club had \"made a commitment to Las Vegas at this point in time and that's where it stands.\" In an interview with [[ESPN]] after returning from a meeting for the [[2016 NFL draft]] he expanded upon reasons why Southern Nevada held a certain appeal over the [[East Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|East Bay]] of the [[San Francisco Bay Area|Oakland\u2013San Francisco Bay Area]], how he tried to make it work in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and why (as he told Sandoval) he hopes to turn Nevada into the \"Silver and Black State\"; he also spoke of the meeting saying, \"It was a positive, well-organized presentation that I believe was well-received\", and stating, \"It was a very positive step in finding the Raiders a home.\"\n\nOn May 20, 2016, [[New England Patriots]] owner [[Robert Kraft]] said he would support Davis and the Raiders move to Las Vegas, stating, \"I think it would be good for the NFL.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Knoblauch|first=Austin|title=Robert Kraft would support Raiders move to Las Vegas|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000664187/article/robert-kraft-would-support-raiders-move-to-las-vegas|publisher=National Football League|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\nIf the Raiders were to move to Las Vegas the only competition they would have is the [[Vegas Golden Knights]] of the [[National Hockey League]]. On August 11, 2016, Raiders officials met with Northern Nevada officials about the possibility of [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] being the site of a new training camp/practice facility and toured several sites including the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], Reno area high schools, and sports complexes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raiders relocation could include Reno training camp|last=Richardson|first=Seth|url=http://www.rgj.com/story/sports/2016/08/10/raiders-relocation-could-include-reno-training-camp/88547986|accessdate=September 24, 2016|work=[[Reno Gazette-Journal]]|date=August 11, 2016}}</ref> On August 25, 2016, the Raiders filed a trademark application for \"Las Vegas Raiders\" on the same day renderings of a new stadium (located west of [[Interstate 15]] at Las Vegas) were released to the public.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez|first=A.J.|title=Oakland Raiders file to trademark 'Las Vegas Raiders' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2016/08/25/raiders-las-vegas-trademark-relocation/89341228/|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2016, the Southern Nevada Tourism Infrastructure Committee unanimously voted to recommend and approve $750&nbsp;million for the Las Vegas stadium plan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stadium plan to lure Raiders to Las Vegas passes vote|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000703280/article/stadium-plan-to-lure-raiders-to-las-vegas-passes-vote|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2016, the [[Nevada Senate]] voted 16\u20135 to approve the funding bill for the Las Vegas stadium proposal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chereb|first1=Sandra|last2=Whaley|first2=Sean|title=Raiders stadium project for Las Vegas clears Nevada Senate in 16\u20135 vote|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/stadium/raiders-stadium-project-las-vegas-clears-nevada-senate-16-5-vote|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|date=October 11, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2016}}</ref> The [[Nevada Assembly]] voted 28\u201313 three days later to approve the bill to fund the new Las Vegas stadium proposal; two days later, Sandoval signed the funding bill into law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas stadium plan gains approval from Nevada Legislature|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000720822/article/las-vegas-stadium-plan-gains-approval-from-nevada-legislature|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=October 14, 2016|accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDavis told [[ESPN]] on October 15, 2016 that even if the Raiders are approved by the league to relocate to the [[Las Vegas metropolitan area]], the club would play the next two seasons at the [[Oakland Alameda Coliseum]] in 2017 and 2018, stating \"We want to bring a Super Bowl championship back to the Bay Area.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Gutierrez|first=Paul|title=Mark Davis: Raiders' Oakland plan unchanged even if Las Vegas deal OK'd|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17802673/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-reiterates-desire-play-coliseum-next-two-years-las-vegas-deal|publisher=ESPN|date=October 15, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> The team originally planned to play at a temporary facility in 2019 after its lease at the Coliseum expired, but they were able to get a two year extension by the Coliseum board in March of 2019, with the second year in 2020 tagged on as insurance in case Allegiant Stadium was not ready in time. Davis had also indicated a desire to play at least one preseason game in Las Vegas, at Sam Boyd Stadium, as early as the 2017 season, but this ultimately never came into fruition.\n\nOn October 17, 2016, Nevada Governor Brian Sandoval signed into law Senate Bill 1 and Assembly Bill 1 which approved a hotel room rate tax increase to accommodate $750&nbsp;million in public funding for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nevada governor signs bill to approve Las Vegas stadium plan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000722987/article/nevada-governor-signs-bill-to-approve-las-vegas-stadium-plan|agency=Associated Press|publisher=National Football League|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=October 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spousta|first=Tom|title=Gov. Brian Sandoval signs Raiders stadium bill \u2013 VIDEO|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/stadium/gov-brian-sandoval-signs-raiders-stadium-bill-video|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=October 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Raiders officially filed paperwork to relocate from Oakland, California, to Las Vegas, Nevada, on January 19, 2017. On January 30, 2017, it was announced that Adelson had dropped out of the stadium project, also withdrawing the Las Vegas Sands' proposed $650&nbsp;million contribution from the project.  Instead, the Raiders would increase their contribution from $500&nbsp;million to $1.15&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adelson no longer involved in Raiders' Las Vegas stadium plan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000781086/article/adelson-no-longer-involved-in-raiders-las-vegas-stadium-plan|publisher=National Football League|date=January 30, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> One day after Adelson's announcement, [[Goldman Sachs]] (the company behind the financing to the proposed Las Vegas stadium) announced its intent to withdraw from the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sources: Financial giant Goldman Sachs backs out of Raiders' stadium deal|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18594904/oakland-raiders-las-vegas-stadium-deal-loses-backing-goldman-sachs|publisher=ESPN|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2017, the Raiders revealed [[Bank of America]] would be replacing the Sheldon Adelson portion of the funding.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raiders secure financing for potential Las Vegas stadium|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000790903/article/raiders-secure-financing-for-potential-las-vegas-stadium|publisher=National Football League|date=March 7, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jon Mark Saraceno|title=Raiders' Las Vegas stadium gets boost from Bank of America|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/nfl-vegas/bank-america-bankroll-raiders-stadium-las-vegas|newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=March 6, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref> On March 27, 2017, the National Football League officially approved the Raiders move from Oakland to Las Vegas in a 31\u20131 vote, ensuring them a new stadium in the process.\n\n====Management style====\nIn his short ownership of the Raiders, Davis has focused on the business aspects of the team while leaving football matters in the hands of general manager [[Reggie McKenzie (linebacker)|Reggie McKenzie]]. This form of management is in stark contrast to his father, who was well known as one of the most hands-on owners in professional sports. Al Davis became general manager of the Raiders in 1966 after returning from a short stint as AFL commissioner, a post he kept after becoming principal owner in 1972. He exercised close control over both business and football matters until his death.\n\nIn 2013, Davis fired the Raiders public relations director because of a ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' article that was critical of Davis' father. Davis stated that the director's replacement needed to understand the importance of his father's legacy and actively protect it.<ref name=\"2013Davis\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9357655/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis-zak-gilbert-exit-no-shot-reggie-mckenzie|title=Raiders' Mark Davis: 'Reggie's fine'|date=June 9, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===On domestic violence in the NFL===\nDavis spoke out publicly on the issue of [[National Football League controversies#Domestic violence|domestic violence in the NFL]], following [[San Francisco 49ers]] defensive lineman [[Ray McDonald]]'s arrest on August 31, 2014.<ref name=\"WA Post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/09/18/raiders-owner-mark-davis-has-an-idea-for-solving-nfls-domestic-violence-crisis/|title=Raiders owner Mark Davis says he can solve the NFL's domestic-violence crisis|author=Cindy Boren|date=September 18, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> Davis disagreed with [[Jed York]]'s decision to keep McDonald on the active roster, proposing that the league should suspend any player arrested with pay while \"the investigation moves forward\"<ref name=\"WA Post\" /> This was the first proposal of this kind following the [[Ray Rice#Personal life|Ray Rice assault video]] surfacing, that specifically called for an immediate suspension of players rather than leaving the decision to suspend up to the respective franchises themselves. In March 2015, Davis again went public on the issue of domestic violence, shutting down rumors that the Raiders' started negotiations with [[Greg Hardy#Domestic abuse|Greg Hardy]], who was convicted on domestic abuse charges earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/mark-davis-is-not-happy-raiders-used-as-greg-hardy-s-leverage-195946487.html|title=Mark Davis is not happy Raiders used as Greg Hardy's leverage|date=March 13, 2015|work=Yahoo Sports|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref> The Raiders' organization has traditionally been vocal about domestic violence issues, with direct involvement with the [[Fred Biletnikoff#Personal life|Tracey Biletnikoff Foundation]], created by Hall of Famer [[Fred Biletnikoff]] to support community substance abuse treatment and domestic violence programs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/may/07/sports/sp-27521|title=Former Raider Star Biletnikoff Honors Deceased Daughter|last=Peterson|first=Anne M.|date=May 7, 2000|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===On social justice and player protests===\nDavis has spoken out publicly on the controversial [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|National Anthem protests]] in the NFL where players kneel during the playing of the pre-game National Anthem to protest social injustice and police brutality on African Americans. Davis originally preferred his players to stand but after comments made by President [[Donald Trump]] calling protesting players \"Sons of Bitches\" and saying they should be fired for kneeling Davis changed his stance in a public statement the following weekend stating \"About a year ago before our Tennessee game I met with [[Derek Carr]] and [[Khalil Mack]] to ask their permission to have [[Tommie Smith]] light the torch for my father before the game in Mexico City,\" Davis told ESPN's Paul Gutierrez. \"I explained to them I was asking their permission because I had previously told them that I would prefer that they not protest while in Raiders uniform. And should they have something to say once their uniform was off, I might go up there with them. Over the last year, though,\" Davis continued, \"the streets have gotten hot and there has been a lot of static in the air and recently fuel has been added to the fire. I can no longer ask our team not to say something while they are in a Raider uniform. The only thing I can ask them to do is do it with class. Do it with pride. Not only do we have to tell people there is something wrong, we have to come up with answers. That's the challenge that's in front of us as Americans and as human beings.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2017/9/24/16357598/mark-davis-i-can-no-longer-ask-our-team-to-not-say-something-while-they-are-in-a-raiders-uniform|title=Mark Davis: \u2018I can no longer ask our team to not say something while they are in a Raider uniform\u2019|work=Silver And Black Pride|access-date=24 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Davis abstained from an NFL owner resolution on the anthem protests that called for players to stand or stay in the locker room until after the anthem is played or face a team fine for kneeling, locking arms or raising their fist. Davis abstained along with [[San Francisco 49ers]] owner [[Jed York]] after speaking out on social justice issues to the other owners.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2018/5/24/17390248/raiders-owner-mark-davis-abstained-owner-vote-on-anthem-resolution-spoke-up-social-justice-issues|title=Mark Davis abstained from owner vote on anthem resolution, spoke up on social justice issues|work=Silver And Black Pride|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/05/24/raiders-mark-davis-confirms-he-abstained-from-anthem-vote/|title=Raiders\u2019 Mark Davis confirms he abstained from anthem vote|date=May 24, 2018|work=The Mercury News|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDavis says he is a food connoisseur and has said that his favorite restaurants include Dan Tana's in Los Angeles, California, Joe's Stone Crab in Miami Beach, Florida, and [[P.F. Chang's]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The TK Show \u2013 Mark Davis \u2013 EP04A|url = https://soundcloud.com/mercurynews/tkshow-mark-davis-ep04a|website = SoundCloud|accessdate = 9 April 2015}}</ref> Davis is known for his signature [[bowl cut|bowl haircut]] and for driving a 1997 [[Dodge Caravan]] SE which is outfitted with a bubble-top Mark III conversion kit as well as a VHS player mounted to the roof.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wickersham |first1=Seth |last2=Van Natta Jr.|first2=Don |title=Sin City Or Bust |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/sin-city-bust/story?id=46773399 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=April 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Keown |first1=Tim |title=Just live up to your dad's name and solve the NFL's L.A. problem, baby! |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> Davis donated $10,000 to the Gridiron [[Political action committee|PAC]] between 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis|title=Get to know Mark Davis, the Oakland Raiders' owner|date=July 16, 2018|website=Sports Illustrated|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131061521/https://www.si.com/nfl/oakland-raiders-owner-mark-davis|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last=Kawakami |first=Tim |title=Oakland Raiders owner Mark Davis makes good first impression |date=January 11, 2012 |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_19712614 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64cb7XWcI?url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_19712614 |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/13735322/are-mark-davis-raiders-leaving-oakland/ Profile piece on Mark Davis done in 2014] from [[ESPN]]\n\n{{Las Vegas Raiders}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders owner navbox}}\n{{NFLOwners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Mark}}\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders owners]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Raiders owners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "name_user": "2601:643:c000:4ae0:4dc7:59ee:49d8:2f49", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added data)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Davis_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Phoenicia University", "text_new": "{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox university \n|name           = PU Phoenicia University <br />\n\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627\n|established    = 2015\n|motto          = \"Leaders aren't born, they are crafted\"\n|type           = [[Nonprofit organization|Non-profit]], [[private university]]\n|president      = Imad Zbib, Ph.D.\n|city           = [[Daoudiye]], [[District of Zahrani]]\n|country        = [[Lebanon]] \n|campus         = [[suburban area|Suburban]], {{convert|25|acre|m2}}\n|website        = [http://www.pu.edu.lb www.pu.edu.lb]\n}}\n'''Phoenicia University '''(PU; {{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627}}) is a [[private University|private]] [[institution of higher education]], with its main campus located in [[Daoudiye]], the [[district of Zahrani]], [[South Governorate]] of [[Lebanon]], a 40-minute drive from [[Beirut International Airport]].<ref>{{ cite web | title = Phoenicia University opens in Zahrani| url = http://www.businessnews.com.lb/cms/Story/StoryDetails/4765/Phoenicia-University-opens-in-Zahrani |accessdate= 4 April 2019 | publisher = BusinessNews.com.lb }}</ref><ref name=\"aljoumhouria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.aljoumhouria.com/news/index/428757|script-title=ar:\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0629\u064f \u0639\u0650\u0644\u0645 \u0648\u0623\u0628\u062d\u0627\u062b \u0641\u064a \u0642\u0644\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0648\u0628|language=ar|trans-title=The University of Venice is a beacon of science and research in the heart of the South|work=Al-Jomjoriah|date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nPhoenicia University was founded in 2012 by Randa Berri, the wife of [[Nabih Berri]], [[List of speakers of the Parliament of Lebanon|the Speaker]] of the [[Lebanese Parliament]]. The location in the south of [[Lebanon]] was chosen for the needs of the growing labor market in the region, from where students would previously have had to travel to [[Beirut]] or another major city, with a higher cost of living. Construction finished in the summer of 2015, and the first 5 of the university's 6 schools began teaching. In the university's first year, it accepted 450 students from 1,200 applications.<ref name=\"al-binaa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-binaa.com/archives/article/101785|script-title=ar:\u0635\u0631\u062d \u062a\u0631\u0628\u0648\u064a\u0651 \u0631\u0627\u0626\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0631\u0641\u0646\u062f \u064a\u0644\u0628\u0651\u064a \u062a\u0637\u0644\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f\u0629|language=ar|trans-title=A leading educational institution in Sarafand meets the ambitions of the younger generations|last=Kharroubi|first=Inam|work=Al-Binaa|date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe main campus of Phoenicia University is located in the district of Zahrani in the Southern Governorate on a land of approximately 25 acres. In addition to classrooms and offices, the main campus provides facilities including libraries, labs, residential accommodation, commercial space, sports courts, a gym, chapel and prayer room.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe university also operates an Administrative Office in the [[Beirut Central District]] that also serves as the university's Executive Education Center.\n\n==Colleges==\nThe University is licensed to operate six colleges with a total of 17 degree programs. The colleges of Engineering, Business Administration, Law and Political Science, Arts and Sciences, and Public Health began operating in the university's first year. The college of Architecture began teaching in September 2016.<ref name=\"al-binaa\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{coord missing|Lebanon}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2012]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox University \n|name           = PU Phoenicia University <br />\n\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627\n|established    = 2015\n|motto          = \"Leaders aren't born, they are crafted\"\n|type           = [[Nonprofit organization|Non-profit]], [[private university]]\n|president      = Imad Zbib, Ph.D.\n|city           = [[Daoudiye]], [[District of Zahrani]]\n|country        = [[Lebanon]] \n|campus         = [[suburban area|Suburban]], {{convert|25|acre|m2}}\n|website        = [http://www.pu.edu.lb www.pu.edu.lb]\n}}\n'''Phoenicia University '''(PU; {{lang-ar|\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627}}) is a [[private University|private]] [[institution of higher education]], with its main campus located in [[Daoudiye]], the [[district of Zahrani]], [[South Governorate]] of [[Lebanon]], a 40-minute drive from [[Beirut International Airport]].<ref>{{ cite web | title = Phoenicia University opens in Zahrani| url = http://www.businessnews.com.lb/cms/Story/StoryDetails/4765/Phoenicia-University-opens-in-Zahrani | |accessdate= 4 April 2019 | publisher = BusinessNews.com.lb }}</ref><ref name=\"aljoumhouria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.aljoumhouria.com/news/index/428757|script-title=ar:\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0633\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0629\u064f \u0639\u0650\u0644\u0645 \u0648\u0623\u0628\u062d\u0627\u062b \u0641\u064a \u0642\u0644\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0648\u0628|language=ar|trans-title=The University of Venice is a beacon of science and research in the heart of the South|work=Al-Jomjoriah|date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nPhoenicia University was founded in 2012 by Randa Berri, the wife of [[Nabih Berri]], [[List of speakers of the Parliament of Lebanon|the Speaker]] of the [[Lebanese Parliament]]. The location in the south of [[Lebanon]] was chosen for the needs of the growing labor market in the region, from where students would previously have had to travel to [[Beirut]] or another major city, with a higher cost of living. Construction finished in the summer of 2015, and the first 5 of the university's 6 schools began teaching. In the university's first year, it accepted 450 students from 1,200 applications.<ref name=\"al-binaa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-binaa.com/archives/article/101785|script-title=ar:\u0635\u0631\u062d \u062a\u0631\u0628\u0648\u064a\u0651 \u0631\u0627\u0626\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0631\u0641\u0646\u062f \u064a\u0644\u0628\u0651\u064a \u062a\u0637\u0644\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f\u0629|language=ar|trans-title=A leading educational institution in Sarafand meets the ambitions of the younger generations|last=Kharroubi|first=Inam|work=Al-Binaa|date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe main campus of Phoenicia University is located in the district of Zahrani in the Southern Governorate on a land of approximately 25 acres. In addition to classrooms and offices, the main campus provides facilities including libraries, labs, residential accommodation, commercial space, sports courts, a gym, chapel and prayer room.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe university also operates an Administrative Office in the [[Beirut Central District]] that also serves as the university's Executive Education Center.\n\n==Colleges==\nThe University is licensed to operate six colleges with a total of 17 degree programs. The colleges of Engineering, Business Administration, Law and Political Science, Arts and Sciences, and Public Health began operating in the university's first year. The college of Architecture began teaching in September 2016.<ref name=\"al-binaa\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{coord missing|Lebanon}}\n\n==External Links==\n* {{official website}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2012]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenicia_University"}
{"title_page": "Pharos University in Alexandria", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2014}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = Pharos University in Alexandria (P.U.A )\n| image = Pharos University.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = Pharos university logo\n|established    = 2006\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n|president      = Prof. Abd Al Monem Mousa\n|vice-president = Prof. Yousry El Kharadly\n|city           = [[Alexandria]]\n|country        = [[Egypt]]\n|campus         = [[Smouha]]\n|website = {{URL|http://www.pua.edu.eg}}\n}}\n'''Pharos University in Alexandria''' ('''PUA''')  \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0643\u0646\u062f\u0631\u064a\u0629 is a non-governmental and profit making [[university]] in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]].\n\nIt obtained the license from the Egyptian Supreme Council of Private Universities to begin operation in the 2006\u20132007 academic year. It includes eleven faculties: [[Pharmacy]] and Drug Manufacturing, [[Dentistry]], [[Engineering]], [[Languages]] and [[Translation]], [[Financial]] and [[Public administration|Administrative Sciences]], [[Legal Studies]] and International Relations, [[Tourism]] and [[Hotel management|Hotel Management]], [[Allied Medical Sciences]], [[Mass Communication]], [[Physical Therapy]], [[Arts]] and [[Design]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pua.edu.eg Pharos University in Alexandria] (English language site\n\n{{coord|31.2077|29.9603|type:edu_region:EG|display=title}}\n\n== Faculty of Allied Medical Sciences ==\n\nIt teaches various science subjects as Physics, Chemistry and anatomy. It connects the general science subjects with medicine based subjects hence the name and contain 8 departments:\n\n* Department of Medical Equipment\n* Department of Medical Laboratory\n* Department of Radiological Sciences And Medical Imaging\n* Department of Nursing\n* Department of Nutrition\n* Department of Optical\n* Department of Prosthodontics\n* Department of Intensive Care and Anesthesia\n\nThe Faculty of Allied Medical Sciences seeks to serve society by providing the knowledge needed for all that is related to human health, through educating and graduating efficient medical technology specialist.\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pharos University In Alexandria}}\n[[Category:Universities in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Egypt]]\n\n\n{{egypt-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2014}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = Pharos University in Alexandria (P.U.A )\n| image = Pharos University.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = Pharos university logo\n|established    = 2006\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n|president      = Prof. Abd Al Monem Mousa\n|vice-president = Prof. Yousry El Kharadly\n|city           = [[Alexandria]]\n|country        = [[Egypt]]\n|campus         = [[Smouha]]\n|website = {{URL|http://www.pua.edu.eg}}\n}}\n'''Pharos University in Alexandria''' ('''PUA''')  \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0643\u0646\u062f\u0631\u064a\u0629 is a non-governmental and profit making [[university]] in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]].\n\nIt obtained the license from the Egyptian Supreme Council of Private Universities to begin operation in the 2006\u20132007 academic year. It includes eleven faculties: [[Pharmacy]] and Drug Manufacturing, [[Dentistry]], [[Engineering]], [[Languages]] and [[Translation]], [[Financial]] and [[Public administration|Administrative Sciences]], [[Legal Studies]] and International Relations, [[Tourism]] and [[Hotel management|Hotel Management]], [[Allied Medical Sciences]], [[Mass Communication]], [[Physical Therapy]], [[Arts]] and [[Design]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pua.edu.eg Pharos University in Alexandria] (English language site\n\n{{coord|31.2077|29.9603|type:edu_region:EG|display=title}}\n\n== Faculty of Allied Medical Sciences ==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pharos University In Alexandria}}\n[[Category:Universities in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Egypt]]\nIt teaches various science subjects as Physics, Chemistry and anatomy. It connects the general science subjects with medicine based subjects hence the name and contain 8 departments:\n\n* Department of Medical Equipment\n* Department of Medical Laboratory\n* Department of Radiological Sciences And Medical Imaging\n* Department of Nursing\n* Department of Nutrition\n* Department of Optical\n* Department of Prosthodontics\n* Department of Intensive Care and Anesthesia\n\nThe Faculty of Allied Medical Sciences seeks to serve society by providing the knowledge needed for all that is related to human health, through educating and graduating efficient medical technology specialist.{{egypt-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFaculty of Allied Medical Sciences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharos_University_in_Alexandria"}
{"title_page": "Lake W\u0101naka", "text_new": "{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake W\u0101naka\n| image = Wanaka from mt roy.jpg\n| caption = View of Lake W\u0101naka from Mt. Roy.\n| image_bathymetry = NZ-L Wanaka.png\n| caption_bathymetry = Location on the [[South Island]]\n| location = [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown-Lakes District]], [[Otago]], [[South Island]]\n| coords = {{coord|44|30|S|169|08|E|region:NZ_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = [[Clutha River]]\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = New Zealand\n| length = {{convert|42|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|192|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = approx. {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|278|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = [[Harwich Island]], [[Mou Tapu]], [[Mou Waho]], [[Ruby Island, Lake W\u0101naka|Ruby Island]], [[Stevensons Island]]\n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake W\u0101naka''' is New Zealand's [[List of lakes in New Zealand#Largest lakes|fourth largest lake]].<ref>[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/destinations/regions/wanaka/wanaka-home.cfm Lake W\u0101naka] (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref> In the [[Otago]] region, it is 278 meters above sea level,<ref>[https://www.orc.govt.nz/managing-our-environment/water/water-monitoring-and-alerts/upper-clutha/Lake-wanaka Otago Regional Council] (Lake level monitoring)</ref> covers {{convert|192|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/otago-places/page-19|title=19. \u2013 Otago places \u2013 Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|last=Taonga|website=www.teara.govt.nz}}</ref>, and is more than {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep. \n\nThe original [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name ''Oanaka'' means 'The place of Anaka', a local tribal chief.<ref name=\"TEARA\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/W/WanakaLake/WanakaLake/en Wanaka, Lake] (from [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]], The 1966 New Zealand Encyclopaedia)</ref>\nThe town near the foot of the lake is called [[Wanaka]].\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Geography===\nLake W\u0101naka lies at the heart of the Otago Lakes in the lower South Island of New Zealand. The township, which sits in a glacier-carved basin on the shores of the lake, is the gateway to [[Mount Aspiring National Park|Mt Aspiring National Park]]. [[Lake H\u0101wea]] is a 15-minute drive away, en route to the frontier town of [[Makarora]], the last stop before the West Coast Glacier region. To the south is the historic [[Cardrona Valley]], a popular scenic alpine route to neighbouring [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].\n\n===Geology===\nAt its greatest extent, which is roughly along a north\u2013south axis, the lake is 42 kilometres long. Its widest point, at the southern end, is 10 kilometres. The lake's western shore is lined with high peaks rising to over 2000 metres above sea level. Along the eastern shore the land is also mountainous, but the peaks are somewhat lower.\n\nLake W\u0101naka lies in a [[u-shaped valley]] formed by [[glacier|glacial]] erosion during the last [[ice age]], more than 10,000 years ago. It is fed by the [[Matukituki River|Matukituki]] and [[Makarora River]]s, and is the source of the [[Clutha River]]. Nearby [[Lake H\u0101wea]] lies in a parallel valley carved by a neighbouring glacier eight kilometres to the east. At their closest point (a rocky ridge called The Neck), the lakes are only 1,000 metres apart.<ref name=\"T2\">[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/sights-activities/scenic-highlights/lakes/sh-lake-wanaka-and-hawea.cfm Lakes: Laka Wanaka and Hawea] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/676ClFFma?url=http://www.newzealand.com/int/article/lakes-wanaka-and-hawea/ |date=2012-04-21 }} (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\nSmall islands towards the foot of the lake include Ruby Island, [[Stevensons Island]] and Harwich Island. Some host ecological sanctuaries, such as one for [[weka|buff weka]] on Stevensons Island.<ref name=\"TVNZ_710786\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/411879/710786 |title=What's Up DOC - Wanaka |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe towns of [[Wanaka]] and [[Albert Town, New Zealand|Albert Town]] are near the lake's outflow into the [[Clutha River]].\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location = Lake W\u0101naka\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| Jan high C = 23.9\n| Feb high C = 23.4\n| Mar high C = 20.8\n| Apr high C = 17.3\n| May high C = 12.2\n| Jun high C = 8.4\n| Jul high C = 8.4\n| Aug high C = 11.0\n| Sep high C = 14.4\n| Oct high C = 16.8\n| Nov high C = 19.8\n| Dec high C = 21.9\n| Jan low C = 10.8\n| Feb low C = 10.4\n| Mar low C = 8.4\n| Apr low C = 5.1\n| May low C = 1.6\n| Jun low C = -0.9\n| Jul low C = -1.2\n| Aug low C = -0.2\n| Sep low C = 2.4\n| Oct low C = 5.0\n| Nov low C = 7.3\n| Dec low C = 9.6\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation mm = 56.9\n| Feb precipitation mm = 50.2\n| Mar precipitation mm = 60.7\n| Apr precipitation mm = 56.4\n| May precipitation mm = 62.7\n| Jun precipitation mm = 54.5\n| Jul precipitation mm = 52.2\n| Aug precipitation mm = 52.8\n| Sep precipitation mm = 56.4\n| Oct precipitation mm = 63.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 54.7\n| Dec precipitation mm = 51.9\n| year precipitation mm = 672.5\n| Jan sun = 231.5\n| Feb sun = 201.7\n| Mar sun = 182.6\n| Apr sun = 164.0\n| May sun = 135.5\n| Jun sun = 120.5\n| Jul sun = 126.6\n| Aug sun = 155.8\n| Sep sun = 172.5\n| Oct sun = 193.8\n| Nov sun = 202.2\n| Dec sun = 212.1\n| year sun = 2098.8\n| source = http://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/content/library/Weather_data.pdf\n}}\n\n==Human history==\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\n\nFor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the Wanaka area was a natural crossroads. The [[Haast Pass]] gave access to the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and its [[pounamu]]; the Cardrona Valley led to the natural rock bridge \"Whatatorere\", which was the only place that the [[Kawarau River]] and [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] could be crossed without boats.<ref name=\"DoC\">{{cite book\n|title=Bannockburn Heritage Landscape Study\n|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/Documents/science-and-technical/SfC244b.pdf\n|date=2004\n|author=Janet Stephenson, Heather Bauchop, and Peter Petchey\n|page=29\n}}</ref> Native reeds were used to build boats that enabled a swift return downriver to the east coast.\n\nThe Cromwell basin supported a large population of [[moa]], which were hunted to extinction about 500 years ago.<ref name=\"DoC\"/>\n\nUntil the early nineteenth century, Wanaka was visited annually by [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] who sought [[pounamu]] in the mountains above the [[Haast River]] and hunted eels and birds over summer, returning to the east coast by descending the [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] in reed boats.<ref name=TeAraOtagoMaori>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n  |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/otago-region/page-4 \n| author=Malcolm McKinnon\n| title=Otago region - M\u0101ori history and whaling\n| encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref>  Ng\u0101i Tahu use of the land was ended by [[History of the Otago Region#Ngati Toa invasions|attacks by North Island tribes]].<ref name=\"DoC\"/> In 1836, the [[Ngati Tama]] chief [[Te Puoho-o-te-rangi|Te Puoho]] led a 100-person war party, armed with muskets, down the West Coast and over the Haast Pass: they fell on the Ng\u0101i Tahu encampment between Lake Wanaka and [[Lake H\u0101wea]], capturing 10 people and killing and eating two children.<ref name=Smith1910>{{cite book\n| title=History and Traditions of the Maoris of the West Coast North Island of New Zealand Prior to 1840\n|author=S Percy Smith\n|date=1910\n|publisher = Polynesian Society\n|location=New Plymouth \n|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-SmiHist-t1-body1-d21-d7.html\n}}</ref> Although Te Puoho was later killed by the southern Ng\u0101i Tahu leader [[Tuhawaiki]],<ref name=AthollAnderson>{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Atholl Anderson\n|title =Te Puoho-o-te-rangi\n|volume =1\n|year=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand \n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t59/te-puoho-o-te-rangi\n|accessdate =2017-07-11}}</ref> Maori seasonal visits to the area ceased.\n\nThe first European to see the lake was Nathaniel Chalmers in 1853.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author=Jock Phillips\n|title=European exploration - Otago and Southland\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/european-exploration/page-7\n|accessdate=2017-07-11\n}}\n</ref> Guided by Reko and Kaikoura, he walked from Tuturau ([[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]) to the lake via the [[Kawarau River]]. However he was stricken by dysentery, so his guides returned him down the Clutha in a reed boat.<ref name=\"TeAraNC\">\n{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Roger Frazer\n|title=Chalmers, Nathanael\n|series=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography \n|volume=1\n|date=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1c11/chalmers-nathanael\n|accessdate=13 July 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nBy 1861, several sheep stations had been established in around the south end of the lake, and in 1862, the lake itself was surveyed in a whaleboat.<ref name=\"TEARA\"/> The early European name was Lake Pembroke.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=OW18890425.2.62&cl=&srpos=0&e=-------10--1----0-all&st=1%7CPASSIM|title=Papers Past - PASSIM NOTES. (Otago Witness, 1889-04-25)|first=National Library of New|last=Zealand|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\n===Current use and tourism===\n[[File:Lake Wanaka.jpg|thumb|244px|right|Lake W\u0101naka on an overcast day.]]\n\nIn addition to ongoing sheep farming, the lake is now a popular resort, and is much used in the summer for [[fishing]], boating and [[human swimming|swimming]]. The nearby mountains and fast-flowing rivers allow for [[Adventure travel|adventure tourism]] year-round, with [[jetboat]]ing and [[skiing]] facilities located nearby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/|title=Wanaka Tourism}}</ref>\n\nThe Wanaka region has been the setting for many international films, including ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/wanaka/the-lord-of-the-rings-location-tarras-and-wanaka|title=The Lord of the Rings Location: Tarras & Wanaka}}</ref> ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newzealand.com/ie/feature/the-hobbit-trilogy-filming-locations/|title=The Hobbit Trilogy Filming Locations}}</ref> the ''Legend of S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/wanaka/chinese-fantasy-filming-wanaka|author=Otago Daily Times|access-date=27 January 2018|title=Chinese fantasy filming in Wanaka|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> and ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/destinations/nz/89336353/witherspoon-winfrey-and-kaling-in-wanaka-and-lake-hawea|title=Witherspoon, Winfrey and Kaling in Wanaka and Lake Hawea}}</ref> Lake W\u0101naka repeatedly featured in the movie ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'' as a location the lead couple visited and as the answer to [[Tom Cruise]]'s question on the phone to verify the identity of his wife. The New Zealand cook and author [[Annabel Langbein]] owns a small estate at the side of the lake and filmed her series ''The Free Range Cook'' and ''Simple Pleasures'' here.\n\nWith [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] airport close by, tourism mirrors that of the surrounding areas.\n\nSadly the Crack Willow Tree, photographed by many, many tourists and other photographers, was cut by vandals in 2020.\n\n===Conservation===\nAs one of the few lakes in the South Island with an unmodified shoreline, the lake is protected by special legislation, the Lake Wanaka Preservation Act of 1973. The Act established a 'Guardians of Lake Wanaka' group, appointed by the Minister of Conservation, which advises on measures to protect the lake.<ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/about-doc/role/corporate-publications/briefings-to-new-ministers-archive/briefing-to-the-incoming-minister-of-conservation-2011/6-institutional-arrangements/6_1-statutory-bodies/ Briefing to the incoming Minister of Conservation 2011 - containing information about Statutory bodies, including the Guardians] (from the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website, Friday 14 December 2012)</ref>\n\nOxygen weed (''[[Lagarosiphon major]]''), an aquarium plant and [[invasive species]] native to Southern Africa, has been a problem in the lake's ecosystem for some time. Attempts to eradicate the weed have not been successful. Substantial [[dredging|suction dredging]] operations have shown promise, but tend to miss isolated spots which then regrow into larger weed beds.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |title= Assessment of the 2005/06 ''Lagarosiphon major'' programme in Lake Wanaka |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090920235224/http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |archivedate= 2009-09-20 }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.20&nbsp;[[Mebibyte|MiB]])}} ([[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] report, June 2006, from the [[Land Information New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Wanaka pan.jpg|600px|View of Lake W\u0101naka, New Zealand}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe name of the lake is referenced in the title of the song ''Lake Wanaka'' by [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Keren Peles]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =\n | date =\n | title = \u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05e4\u05dc\u05e1 - \u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05e7\u05d4 (\u05e7\u05dc\u05d9\u05e4)\n | trans-title = Keren Peles - Lake Wanaka (video music)\n | medium =\n | language = he\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9prCgt9xXM\n | access-date =\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | format =\n | time =\n | location =\n | publisher =\n | id =\n | isbn =\n | oclc =\n | quote =\n | ref =\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lakes of New Zealand]]\n*[[List of lakes in New Zealand]]\n*[[Otago Region#Geography|Otago Geography]]\n*[[Sentinel Peak (New Zealand)]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:W\u0101naka, Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Otago]]\n[[Category:Wanaka]]\n[[Category:Clutha River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Lake W\u0101naka\n| image = Wanaka from mt roy.jpg\n| caption = View of Lake W\u0101naka from Mt. Roy.\n| image_bathymetry = NZ-L Wanaka.png\n| caption_bathymetry = Location on the [[South Island]]\n| location = [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown-Lakes District]], [[Otago]], [[South Island]]\n| coords = {{coord|44|30|S|169|08|E|region:NZ_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = [[Clutha River]]\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = New Zealand\n| length = {{convert|42|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|192|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = approx. {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|278|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = [[Harwich Island]], [[Mou Tapu]], [[Mou Waho]], [[Ruby Island, Lake W\u0101naka|Ruby Island]], [[Stevensons Island]]\n| cities = \n}}\n\n'''Lake W\u0101naka''' is New Zealand's [[List of lakes in New Zealand#Largest lakes|fourth largest lake]].<ref>[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/destinations/regions/wanaka/wanaka-home.cfm Lake W\u0101naka] (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref> In the [[Otago]] region, it is 278 meters above sea level,<ref>[https://www.orc.govt.nz/managing-our-environment/water/water-monitoring-and-alerts/upper-clutha/Lake-wanaka Otago Regional Council] (Lake level monitoring)</ref> covers {{convert|192|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/otago-places/page-19|title=19. \u2013 Otago places \u2013 Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|last=Taonga|website=www.teara.govt.nz}}</ref>, and is more than {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep. \n\nThe original [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name ''Oanaka'' means 'The place of Anaka', a local tribal chief.<ref name=\"TEARA\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/W/WanakaLake/WanakaLake/en Wanaka, Lake] (from [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]], The 1966 New Zealand Encyclopaedia)</ref>\nThe town near the foot of the lake is called [[Wanaka]].\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Geography===\nLake W\u0101naka lies at the heart of the Otago Lakes in the lower South Island of New Zealand. The township, which sits in a glacier-carved basin on the shores of the lake, is the gateway to [[Mount Aspiring National Park|Mt Aspiring National Park]]. [[Lake H\u0101wea]] is a 15-minute drive away, en route to the frontier town of [[Makarora]], the last stop before the West Coast Glacier region. To the south is the historic [[Cardrona Valley]], a popular scenic alpine route to neighbouring [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].\n\n===Geology===\nAt its greatest extent, which is roughly along a north\u2013south axis, the lake is 42 kilometres long. Its widest point, at the southern end, is 10 kilometres. The lake's western shore is lined with high peaks rising to over 2000 metres above sea level. Along the eastern shore the land is also mountainous, but the peaks are somewhat lower.\n\nLake W\u0101naka lies in a [[u-shaped valley]] formed by [[glacier|glacial]] erosion during the last [[ice age]], more than 10,000 years ago. It is fed by the [[Matukituki River|Matukituki]] and [[Makarora River]]s, and is the source of the [[Clutha River]]. Nearby [[Lake H\u0101wea]] lies in a parallel valley carved by a neighbouring glacier eight kilometres to the east. At their closest point (a rocky ridge called The Neck), the lakes are only 1,000 metres apart.<ref name=\"T2\">[http://www.newzealand.com/travel/sights-activities/scenic-highlights/lakes/sh-lake-wanaka-and-hawea.cfm Lakes: Laka Wanaka and Hawea] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/676ClFFma?url=http://www.newzealand.com/int/article/lakes-wanaka-and-hawea/ |date=2012-04-21 }} (from the [[Tourism New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\nSmall islands towards the foot of the lake include Ruby Island, [[Stevensons Island]] and Harwich Island. Some host ecological sanctuaries, such as one for [[weka|buff weka]] on Stevensons Island.<ref name=\"TVNZ_710786\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/411879/710786 |title=What's Up DOC - Wanaka |work=[[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe towns of [[Wanaka]] and [[Albert Town, New Zealand|Albert Town]] are near the lake's outflow into the [[Clutha River]].\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location = Lake W\u0101naka\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| Jan high C = 23.9\n| Feb high C = 23.4\n| Mar high C = 20.8\n| Apr high C = 17.3\n| May high C = 12.2\n| Jun high C = 8.4\n| Jul high C = 8.4\n| Aug high C = 11.0\n| Sep high C = 14.4\n| Oct high C = 16.8\n| Nov high C = 19.8\n| Dec high C = 21.9\n| Jan low C = 10.8\n| Feb low C = 10.4\n| Mar low C = 8.4\n| Apr low C = 5.1\n| May low C = 1.6\n| Jun low C = -0.9\n| Jul low C = -1.2\n| Aug low C = -0.2\n| Sep low C = 2.4\n| Oct low C = 5.0\n| Nov low C = 7.3\n| Dec low C = 9.6\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation mm = 56.9\n| Feb precipitation mm = 50.2\n| Mar precipitation mm = 60.7\n| Apr precipitation mm = 56.4\n| May precipitation mm = 62.7\n| Jun precipitation mm = 54.5\n| Jul precipitation mm = 52.2\n| Aug precipitation mm = 52.8\n| Sep precipitation mm = 56.4\n| Oct precipitation mm = 63.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 54.7\n| Dec precipitation mm = 51.9\n| year precipitation mm = 672.5\n| Jan sun = 231.5\n| Feb sun = 201.7\n| Mar sun = 182.6\n| Apr sun = 164.0\n| May sun = 135.5\n| Jun sun = 120.5\n| Jul sun = 126.6\n| Aug sun = 155.8\n| Sep sun = 172.5\n| Oct sun = 193.8\n| Nov sun = 202.2\n| Dec sun = 212.1\n| year sun = 2098.8\n| source = http://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/content/library/Weather_data.pdf\n}}\n\n==Human history==\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\n\nFor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the Wanaka area was a natural crossroads. The [[Haast Pass]] gave access to the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]] and its [[pounamu]]; the Cardrona Valley led to the natural rock bridge \"Whatatorere\", which was the only place that the [[Kawarau River]] and [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] could be crossed without boats.<ref name=\"DoC\">{{cite book\n|title=Bannockburn Heritage Landscape Study\n|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/Documents/science-and-technical/SfC244b.pdf\n|date=2004\n|author=Janet Stephenson, Heather Bauchop, and Peter Petchey\n|page=29\n}}</ref> Native reeds were used to build boats that enabled a swift return downriver to the east coast.\n\nThe Cromwell basin supported a large population of [[moa]], which were hunted to extinction about 500 years ago.<ref name=\"DoC\"/>\n\nUntil the early nineteenth century, W\u0101naka was visited annually by [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] who sought [[pounamu]] in the mountains above the [[Haast River]] and hunted eels and birds over summer, returning to the east coast by descending the [[Clutha River|Clutha River / Mata-Au]] in reed boats.<ref name=TeAraOtagoMaori>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n  |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/otago-region/page-4 \n| author=Malcolm McKinnon\n| title=Otago region - M\u0101ori history and whaling\n| encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref>  Ng\u0101i Tahu use of the land was ended by [[History of the Otago Region#Ngati Toa invasions|attacks by North Island tribes]].<ref name=\"DoC\"/> In 1836, the [[Ngati Tama]] chief [[Te Puoho-o-te-rangi|Te Puoho]] led a 100-person war party, armed with muskets, down the West Coast and over the Haast Pass: they fell on the Ng\u0101i Tahu encampment between Lake Wanaka and [[Lake H\u0101wea]], capturing 10 people and killing and eating two children.<ref name=Smith1910>{{cite book\n| title=History and Traditions of the Maoris of the West Coast North Island of New Zealand Prior to 1840\n|author=S Percy Smith\n|date=1910\n|publisher = Polynesian Society\n|location=New Plymouth \n|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-SmiHist-t1-body1-d21-d7.html\n}}</ref> Although Te Puoho was later killed by the southern Ng\u0101i Tahu leader [[Tuhawaiki]],<ref name=AthollAnderson>{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Atholl Anderson\n|title =Te Puoho-o-te-rangi\n|volume =1\n|year=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand \n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t59/te-puoho-o-te-rangi\n|accessdate =2017-07-11}}</ref> Maori seasonal visits to the area ceased.\n\nThe first European to see the lake was Nathaniel Chalmers in 1853.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author=Jock Phillips\n|title=European exploration - Otago and Southland\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/european-exploration/page-7\n|accessdate=2017-07-11\n}}\n</ref> Guided by Reko and Kaikoura, he walked from Tuturau ([[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]) to the lake via the [[Kawarau River]]. However he was stricken by dysentery, so his guides returned him down the Clutha in a reed boat.<ref name=\"TeAraNC\">\n{{cite encyclopedia\n|author=Roger Frazer\n|title=Chalmers, Nathanael\n|series=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography \n|volume=1\n|date=1990\n|encyclopedia=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1c11/chalmers-nathanael\n|accessdate=13 July 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nBy 1861, several sheep stations had been established in around the south end of the lake, and in 1862, the lake itself was surveyed in a whaleboat.<ref name=\"TEARA\"/> The early European name was Lake Pembroke.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=OW18890425.2.62&cl=&srpos=0&e=-------10--1----0-all&st=1%7CPASSIM|title=Papers Past - PASSIM NOTES. (Otago Witness, 1889-04-25)|first=National Library of New|last=Zealand|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\n===Current use and tourism===\n[[File:Lake Wanaka.jpg|thumb|244px|right|Lake W\u0101naka on an overcast day.]]\n\nIn addition to ongoing sheep farming, the lake is now a popular resort, and is much used in the summer for [[fishing]], boating and [[human swimming|swimming]]. The nearby mountains and fast-flowing rivers allow for [[Adventure travel|adventure tourism]] year-round, with [[jetboat]]ing and [[skiing]] facilities located nearby.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lakewanaka.co.nz/|title=Wanaka Tourism}}</ref>\n\nThe Wanaka region has been the setting for many international films, including ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/wanaka/the-lord-of-the-rings-location-tarras-and-wanaka|title=The Lord of the Rings Location: Tarras & Wanaka}}</ref> ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newzealand.com/ie/feature/the-hobbit-trilogy-filming-locations/|title=The Hobbit Trilogy Filming Locations}}</ref> the ''Legend of S'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/wanaka/chinese-fantasy-filming-wanaka|author=Otago Daily Times|access-date=27 January 2018|title=Chinese fantasy filming in Wanaka|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> and ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/destinations/nz/89336353/witherspoon-winfrey-and-kaling-in-wanaka-and-lake-hawea|title=Witherspoon, Winfrey and Kaling in Wanaka and Lake Hawea}}</ref> Lake W\u0101naka repeatedly featured in the movie ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'' as a location the lead couple visited and as the answer to [[Tom Cruise]]'s question on the phone to verify the identity of his wife. The New Zealand cook and author [[Annabel Langbein]] owns a small estate at the side of the lake and filmed her series ''The Free Range Cook'' and ''Simple Pleasures'' here.\n\nWith [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] airport close by, tourism mirrors that of the surrounding areas.\n\nSadly the Crack Willow Tree, photographed by many, many tourists and other photographers, was cut by vandals in 2020.\n\n===Conservation===\nAs one of the few lakes in the South Island with an unmodified shoreline, the lake is protected by special legislation, the Lake Wanaka Preservation Act of 1973. The Act established a 'Guardians of Lake Wanaka' group, appointed by the Minister of Conservation, which advises on measures to protect the lake.<ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/about-doc/role/corporate-publications/briefings-to-new-ministers-archive/briefing-to-the-incoming-minister-of-conservation-2011/6-institutional-arrangements/6_1-statutory-bodies/ Briefing to the incoming Minister of Conservation 2011 - containing information about Statutory bodies, including the Guardians] (from the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website, Friday 14 December 2012)</ref>\n\nOxygen weed (''[[Lagarosiphon major]]''), an aquarium plant and [[invasive species]] native to Southern Africa, has been a problem in the lake's ecosystem for some time. Attempts to eradicate the weed have not been successful. Substantial [[dredging|suction dredging]] operations have shown promise, but tend to miss isolated spots which then regrow into larger weed beds.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |title= Assessment of the 2005/06 ''Lagarosiphon major'' programme in Lake Wanaka |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090920235224/http://www.linz.govt.nz/docs/crownproperty/biosecurity/lake-wanaka-assessment-2006.pdf |archivedate= 2009-09-20 }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.20&nbsp;[[Mebibyte|MiB]])}} ([[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] report, June 2006, from the [[Land Information New Zealand]] website)</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Wanaka pan.jpg|600px|View of Lake W\u0101naka, New Zealand}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe name of the lake is referenced in the title of the song ''Lake Wanaka'' by [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Keren Peles]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =\n | date =\n | title = \u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05e4\u05dc\u05e1 - \u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05e7\u05d4 (\u05e7\u05dc\u05d9\u05e4)\n | trans-title = Keren Peles - Lake Wanaka (video music)\n | medium =\n | language = he\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9prCgt9xXM\n | access-date =\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | format =\n | time =\n | location =\n | publisher =\n | id =\n | isbn =\n | oclc =\n | quote =\n | ref =\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lakes of New Zealand]]\n*[[List of lakes in New Zealand]]\n*[[Otago Region#Geography|Otago Geography]]\n*[[Sentinel Peak (New Zealand)]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:W\u0101naka, Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Otago]]\n[[Category:Wanaka]]\n[[Category:Clutha River]]\n", "name_user": "2407:7000:9605:fb00:5d67:417c:f637:280f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExploration and settlement)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_W%C4%81naka"}
